ts\">{{cite web |url=https://screenrant.com/pixar-soul-new-facts-information/ |title=Everything We Know (So Far) About Pixar's Soul |last=Sherlock |first=Ben |work=[[ScreenRant]] |date=October 13, 2019 |url-status=live |access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"D23\">{{cite web |url=https://www.thewrap.com/soul-jamie-foxx-and-tina-fey-star-in-pixars-most-existential-adventure-yet/ |title=\u2018Soul': Jamie Foxx and Tina Fey Star in Pixar\u2019s Most Existential Adventure Yet |last=Fuster |first=Jeremy |work=[[The Wrap]] |date=August 24, 2019 |url-status=live |access-date=August 24, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824190938/https://www.thewrap.com/soul-jamie-foxx-and-tina-fey-star-in-pixars-most-existential-adventure-yet/ |archive-date=August 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Polygon\">{{cite web |last1=Radulovic |first1=Petrana |title=Pixar\u2019s latest film Soul is a metaphysical comedy with the studio\u2019s first black lead |url=https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/24/20827001/pixar-soul-jamie-foxx-cast-plot-description |website=[[Polygon.com]] |date=August 24, 2019 |access-date=August 25, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190824231223/https://www.polygon.com/2019/8/24/20827001/pixar-soul-jamie-foxx-cast-plot-description |archive-date=August 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"DisInsiderTwitter\">{{cite tweet |user=TheDisInsider |number=1165330591291568128 |title=\u2018Soul\u2019 will feature music from John Batiste and original score from Trent Reznor & Atticus Ross. Questlove from The Roots will be playing a Jazz Drummer, Phylicia Rashad plays Joe\u2019s mother, Daveed Diggs also starring, as well as Tina Fey and Jamie Foxx. |date=August 24, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"TeaserTrailer\">{{cite tweet |user=TheDisInsider |number=1192183032314073088 |title=First trailer for Disney\u2022Pixar\u2019s \u2018Soul\u2019 debuts tomorrow! |date=November 6, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"ReleasePushBack\">{{cite news|last=Fuster|first=Jeremy|url=https://www.thewrap.com/disney-moves-soul-raya-and-the-last-dragon-release-dates/|title=Disney Moves 'Soul,' 'Raya and the Last Dragon' Release Dates|work=[[TheWrap]]|date=April 13, 2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official|https://movies.disney.com/soul}}\n*{{IMDb title|tt2948372}}\n\n{{Disney theatrical animated features}}\n{{Pixar}}\n{{Pete Docter}}\n{{Tina Fey}}\n\n[[Category:2020 computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:2020 films]]\n[[Category:2020s animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s American animated films]]\n[[Category:2020s fantasy films]]\n[[Category:African-American animated films]]\n[[Category:African-American films]]\n[[Category:American 3D films]]\n[[Category:American computer-animated films]]\n[[Category:American fantasy films]]\n[[Category:American ghost films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films about reincarnation]]\n[[Category:Films about the afterlife]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Pete Docter]]\n[[Category:Films postponed due to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Atticus Ross]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Trent Reznor]]\n[[Category:Films set in New York City]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Pete Docter]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Tina Fey]]\n[[Category:Jazz films]]\n[[Category:Pixar animated films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming English-language films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:Walt Disney Pictures films]]\n", "name_user": "Call me when you get the chance", "label": "safe", "comment": "Restore data that was unexplainedly removed", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Soul_(2020_film)"}
{"title_page": "Wilhelm Valentiner", "text_new": "'''Wilhelm Reinhold Valentiner''' (May 2, 1880 \u2013 September 6, 1958) was a [[Germans|German-American]] [[Art history|art historian]], [[art critic]] and [[museum]] administrator. He was educated and trained in Europe, first working at the [[Mauritshuis]] in [[The Hague]] and at museums in [[Berlin]].\n\nIn 1907 he moved to the United States to become the first [[curator]] of the department of [[decorative arts]] in the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art|Metropolitan Museum]] in [[New York City]]. After returning to Europe to serve in the German Army in World War I, Valentiner later was appointed to other positions in the US. From the mid-1920s, he strongly influenced the development of museum administration in the United States. \n\nHe served as director of the [[Detroit Institute of Art]] in [[Michigan]], from 1924 to 1945. Valentiner became a naturalized US citizen about 1930 and lived in the country for nearly half his life in total. During the early 1930s, he commissioned Mexican artist [[Diego Rivera]] to create a 27-panel mural series about Detroit industry for an interior court of the museum, and gained the patronage of [[Edsel Ford]] for the project.  While controversial in content, the work attracted thousands of new visitors and led to the museum being granted a larger budget by the city. \n\nValentiner is especially known for his writings on [[Flemish people|Flemish]] and [[Dutch people|Dutch]] painting.<ref>''The Passionate Eye: The Life of William Valentiner,'' by Margaret Stearns, Wayne University Press,1980</ref> \n\n==Life==\nWilhelm Valentiner was born at [[Karlsruhe]] (Baden) and attended local schools. He studied at [[Heidelberg]] under [[Henry Thode]], and in the [[Netherlands]] with [[Cornelis Hofstede de Groot]] and with [[Abraham Bredius]]. He served as the latter's assistant at the [[Mauritshuis|Gallery of The Hague]] (Mauritshuis).\n\nIn 1905 he was called to [[Berlin]] by [[Wilhelm von Bode|William Bode]], under whom he worked at the [[Kaiser Friedrich Museum]] and the [[Kunstgewerbemuseum Berlin]]. In 1906 he published his dissertation on [[Rembrandt]], which he had started in 1904: ''Rembrandt auf der Lateinschule''.\n\n;New York City\nIn 1907 he was appointed as the first [[curator]] of the department of [[decorative arts]] in the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art|Metropolitan Museum]] in [[New York City]]. Under his supervision, this department became one of the foremost in the world.\n\n;World War I\nAt the start of [[World War I]], Valentiner returned to Germany to serve in the army. After service at the front in 1916, he was appointed to the [[General Staff|general staff]] in Berlin.\n\n==American museums==\nFollowing the end of the war, Valentiner was offered a position in [[Detroit, Michigan]], where he served for more than two decades. He became a naturalized American citizen around 1930 and lived in the United States for the remainder of his life. \n\n;Detroit\n\nFrom 1924-1945 he was appointed first as advisor and then Director of the [[Detroit Institute of Arts]], one of the cultural institutions that expanded during the city's boom years. The museum was founded as the [[wikidata:Q74861306|Detroit Museum of Art]] in 1885, and was renamed Detroit Institute of Arts in 1919.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Peck|first=William|title=The Detroit Institute of Arts: A brief history.|publisher=Detroit Institute of Arts and Wayne State University Press|year=1991|isbn=9780895581365|location=Detroit|pages=}}</ref> Under his leadership the museum developed into one of the leading art institutions in the United States. His acquisitions and exhibitions in Detroit were products of his wide-ranging scholarship. He was a friend of [[Edsel Ford]] and conducted private seminars on the history of art for Ford's family. \n\nHe commissioned Mexican artist [[Diego Rivera]] to create a series of murals after having seen his work in [[San Francisco, California]]. He convinced Ford to be a patron and underwrite the cost of the murals. Titled ''[[Detroit Industry]]'', they were revolutionary in content for Detroit at the time and generated considerable local controversy. \n\nValentiner developed an expert staff of curators, a vision of an encyclopedic collection, and the museum as a resource for the city, the state, and the Midwest. In 1945 he had to resign from his post in Detroit due to a city age restriction in the civil service.\n\n;Los Angeles\nHe was instrumental in the development of both the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] and the [[J. Paul Getty Museum]].{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}<!-- In what ways did he contribute to the development of these? -->\n\n;North Carolina\nIn 1955 Valentiner was appointed as the first Director of the [[North Carolina Museum of Art]] in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], the capital. He held this position until his death in September 1958.\n\n;References\n<ref>''The Passionate Eye: The Life of William Valentiner'' by Margaret Stearns, Wayne University Press,1980</ref><ref>''The Detroit Institute of Arts: a Brief History'' by William H. Peck, Wayne University Press, 1991</ref>\n\n==Works==\nWilhelm Valentiner published:\n* ''Rembrandt auf der Lateinschule'', Jahrbuch der preu\u00dfischen Kunstsammlungen 27 (1906)\n* ''[[Rembrandt]]'' (1907), with [[Wilhelm von Bode|Bode]]\n* ''Altholl\u00e4ndische Genre Zeichungen'' (1908), with Bode\n* ''[[Rembrandt catalog raisonn\u00e9, 1908|Rembrandt : des Meisters Gem\u00e4lde in 643 Abbildungen]]'' (1908), with [[Adolf Rosenberg]]\n* ''The Art of the Low Countries'' (1914)\n* ''The Last Years of [[Michelangelo]]'' (1914)\n* ''[[Rembrandt]]: wiedergefundene Gem\u00e4lde, 1910-1922, in 128 Abbildungen'' (1923)  \n* ''[[Frans Hals]], des Meisters Gem\u00e4lde in 322 Abbildungen'', Zweite, Neu Bearbeitete Auflage, Deutsche Verlags-Anstalt Stuttgart, Berlin, und Leipzig, 1923\n* ''Frans Hals paintings in America'', 1936\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Rembrandt catalog raisonn\u00e9, 1908}}\n{{Commons|Frans Hals catalog raisonn\u00e9, 1923}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Wilhelm Valentiner}}\n*[https://archive.org/search.php?query=Valentiner Downloadable books by Valentiner], Internet Archive\n*[http://arthistorians.info/valentinerw Biography], ''[[Dictionary of Art Historians]]''\n\n{{NIE}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valentiner, Wilhelm}}\n[[Category:German art historians]]\n[[Category:German curators]]\n[[Category:Museum directors]]\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Detroit Institute of Arts]]\n[[Category:People associated with the J. Paul Getty Museum]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Los Angeles County Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:People from Karlsruhe]]\n[[Category:People from the Grand Duchy of Baden]]\n[[Category:20th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:Rembrandt scholars]]\n[[Category:Scholars of Dutch art]]\n[[Category:Scholars of Netherlandish art]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:German expatriates in the Netherlands]]\n", "text_old": "'''Wilhelm Reinhold Valentiner''' (May 2, 1880 \u2013 September 6, 1958) was a [[Germans|German-American]] [[Art history|art historian]], [[art critic]] and [[museum]] administrator. He was educated and trained in Europe, first working at the [[Mauritshuis]] in [[The Hague]] and at museums in [[Berlin]].\n\nIn 1907 he moved to the United States to become the first [[curator]] of the department of [[decorative arts]] in the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art|Metropolitan Museum]] in [[New York City]]. After returning to Europe to serve in the German Army in World War I, Valentiner later was appointed to other positions in the US. From the mid-1920s, he strongly influenced the development of museum administration in the United States. \n\nHe served as director of the [[Detroit Institute of Art]] in [[Michigan]], from 1924 to 1945. Valentiner became a naturalized US citizen about 1930 and lived in the country for nearly half his life in total. During the early 1930s, he commissioned Mexican artist [[Diego Rivera]] to create a 27-panel mural series about Detroit industry for an interior court of the museum, and gained the patronage of [[Edsel Ford]] for the project.  While controversial in content, the work attracted thousands of new visitors and led to the museum being granted a larger budget by the city. \n\nValentiner is especially known for his writings on [[Flemish people|Flemish]] and [[Dutch people|Dutch]] painting.<ref>''The Passionate Eye: The Life of William Valentiner,'' by Margaret Stearns, Wayne University Press,1980</ref> \n\n==Life==\nWilhelm Valentiner was born at [[Karlsruhe]] (Baden) and attended local schools. He studied at [[Heidelberg]] under [[Henry Thode]], and in the [[Netherlands]] with [[Cornelis Hofstede de Groot]] and with [[Abraham Bredius]]. He served as the latter's assistant at the [[Mauritshuis|Gallery of The Hague]] (Mauritshuis).\n\nIn 1905 he was called to [[Berlin]] by [[Wilhelm von Bode|William Bode]], under whom he worked at the [[Kaiser Friedrich Museum]] and the [[Kunstgewerbemuseum Berlin]]. In 1906 he published his dissertation on [[Rembrandt]], which he had started in 1904: ''Rembrandt auf der Lateinschule''.\n\n;New York City\nIn 1907 he was appointed as the first [[curator]] of the department of [[decorative arts]] in the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art|Metropolitan Museum]] in [[New York City]]. Under his supervision, this department became one of the foremost in the world.\n\n;World War I\nAt the start of [[World War I]], Valentiner returned to Germany to serve in the army. After service at the front in 1916, he was appointed to the [[General Staff|general staff]] in Berlin.\n\n==American museums==\nFollowing the end of the war, Valentiner was offered a position in [[Detroit, Michigan]], where he served for more than two decades. He became a naturalized American citizen around 1930 and lived in the United States for the remainder of his life. \n\n;Detroit\nFrom 1924-1945 he was appointed first as advisor and then Director of the Detroit Museum of Art, one of the cultural institutions that expanded during the city's boom years. It was renamed as the [[Detroit Institute of Arts]]. Under his leadership the museum developed into one of the leading art institutions in the United States. His acquisitions and exhibitions in Detroit were products of his wide-ranging scholarship. He was a friend of [[Edsel Ford]] and conducted private seminars on the history of art for Ford's family. \n\nHe commissioned Mexican artist [[Diego Rivera]] to create a series of murals after having seen his work in [[San Francisco, California]]. He convinced Ford to be a patron and underwrite the cost of the murals. Titled ''[[Detroit Industry]]'', they were revolutionary in content for Detroit at the time and generated considerable local controversy. \n\nValentiner developed an expert staff of curators, a vision of an encyclopedic collection, and the museum as a resource for the city, the state, and the Midwest. In 1945 he had to resign from his post in Detroit due to a city age restriction in the civil service.\n\n;Los Angeles\nHe was instrumental in the development of both the [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]] and the [[J. Paul Getty Museum]].{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}<!-- In what ways did he contribute to the development of these? -->\n\n;North Carolina\nIn 1955 Valentiner was appointed as the first Director of the [[North Carolina Museum of Art]] in [[Raleigh, North Carolina|Raleigh]], the capital. He held this position until his death in September 1958.\n\n;References\n<ref>''The Passionate Eye: The Life of William Valentiner'' by Margaret Stearns, Wayne University Press,1980</ref><ref>''The Detroit Institute of Arts: a Brief History'' by William H. Peck, Wayne University Press, 1991</ref>\n\n==Works==\nWilhelm Valentiner published:\n* ''Rembrandt auf der Lateinschule'', Jahrbuch der preu\u00dfischen Kunstsammlungen 27 (1906)\n* ''[[Rembrandt]]'' (1907), with [[Wilhelm von Bode|Bode]]\n* ''Altholl\u00e4ndische Genre Zeichungen'' (1908), with Bode\n* ''[[Rembrandt catalog raisonn\u00e9, 1908|Rembrandt : des Meisters Gem\u00e4lde in 643 Abbildungen]]'' (1908), with [[Adolf Rosenberg]]\n* ''The Art of the Low Countries'' (1914)\n* ''The Last Years of [[Michelangelo]]'' (1914)\n* ''[[Rembrandt]]: wiedergefundene Gem\u00e4lde, 1910-1922, in 128 Abbildungen'' (1923)  \n* ''[[Frans Hals]], des Meisters Gem\u00e4lde in 322 Abbildungen'', Zweite, Neu Bearbeitete Auflage, Deutsche Verlags-Anstalt Stuttgart, Berlin, und Leipzig, 1923\n* ''Frans Hals paintings in America'', 1936\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons|Rembrandt catalog raisonn\u00e9, 1908}}\n{{Commons|Frans Hals catalog raisonn\u00e9, 1923}}\n* {{Internet Archive author |sname=Wilhelm Valentiner}}\n*[https://archive.org/search.php?query=Valentiner Downloadable books by Valentiner], Internet Archive\n*[http://arthistorians.info/valentinerw Biography], ''[[Dictionary of Art Historians]]''\n\n{{NIE}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Valentiner, Wilhelm}}\n[[Category:German art historians]]\n[[Category:German curators]]\n[[Category:Museum directors]]\n[[Category:1880 births]]\n[[Category:1958 deaths]]\n[[Category:German male non-fiction writers]]\n[[Category:German military personnel of World War I]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Detroit Institute of Arts]]\n[[Category:People associated with the J. Paul Getty Museum]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Los Angeles County Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:People associated with the Metropolitan Museum of Art]]\n[[Category:People from Karlsruhe]]\n[[Category:People from the Grand Duchy of Baden]]\n[[Category:20th-century German writers]]\n[[Category:Rembrandt scholars]]\n[[Category:Scholars of Dutch art]]\n[[Category:Scholars of Netherlandish art]]\n[[Category:German emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:German expatriates in the Netherlands]]\n", "name_user": "Weadock313", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added citation and dates for Detroit Museum of Art.  The museum changed its name in 1919 before Valentiner's involvement.  See PECK", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wilhelm_Valentiner"}
{"title_page": "West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Kasabian]]\n| cover      = Westryderpauperlunaticasylum.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 5 June 2009\n| recorded   = {{plainlist|\n* Orangutan Studios ([[Greensboro, North Carolina]])\n* E-Land Mig Studios ([[Earl Shilton, Leicestershire]])\n* Lookout Studios ([[San Francisco, California]])\n}}\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Indie rock]]<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/news/kasabian-planning-special-festival-slots|title=Kasabian Planning Special Festival Slots|work=[[Clash Magazine|Clash]]''|accessdate=12 March 2011}}</ref>\n* [[psychedelic rock]]<ref name =\"NME\"/>\n* [[space rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/09/album-review-kasabian-velociraptor/|title= Kasabian - Velociraptor!|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=December 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[experimental rock]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gigwise.com/reviews/51157/kasabian---west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum-sony-080609|title=KASABIAN - 'WEST RYDER PAUPER LUNATIC ASYLUM' (SONY) 08/06/09|website=[[Gigwise]]|accessdate=December 29, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = 51:59\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n* [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n* [[Kasabian|Paradise]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Dan the Automator]]\n* [[Sergio Pizzorno]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Empire (Kasabian album)|Empire]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Velociraptor!]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Fire (Kasabian song)|Fire]]\n | single1date = 1 June 2009\n | single2     = [[Where Did All the Love Go?]]\n | single2date = 17 August 2009\n | single3     = [[Underdog (Kasabian song)|Underdog]]\n | single3date = 26 October 2009\n | single4     = [[Vlad the Impaler (song)|Vlad the Impaler]]\n | single4date = 14 February 2010\n}}\n}}\n'''''West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum''''' is the third studio album by British [[indie rock]]<ref name=\"Clash\"/> band [[Kasabian]], which was released on 5 June 2009. It is also the first album by the band to not feature [[Christopher Karloff]], the band's lead guitarist and songwriter, following his departure during the writing stages of Kasabian's second album, ''[[Empire (Kasabian album)|Empire]]'' (2006). The rhythm guitarist [[Sergio Pizzorno]] took over as the main force behind the band's songwriting.\n\nThe album was nominated for the 2009 [[Mercury Prize]]. In October 2009, it was voted the best album of the year by [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' Magazine]].\n\n==History==\n\"Vlad the Impaler\" was made available as a free download from the official website from 31 March to 3 April 2009. The first proper, physical release from the album was \"[[Fire (Kasabian song)|Fire]]\", which was released on 1 June.<ref>[http://blog.kasabian.co.uk/post/89685282/vlad-the-impaler-free-download]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525030141/http://blog.kasabian.co.uk/post/89685282/vlad-the-impaler-free-download |date=25 May 2009 }}</ref> [[Sergio Pizzorno]] has called the 52-minute album \"the soundtrack to an imaginary movie.\" The album includes a duet, on the track \"West Ryder Silver Bullet\", with the actress [[Rosario Dawson]]. The album entered the [[UK Album Chart]] at No. 1, giving the band their second No. 1 album.\n\"Underdog\" has been used by [[Sony]] in a commercial for their [[BRAVIA]] Televisions.<ref name=\"Bravia-commercial\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvadmusic.co.uk/2009/02/sony-bravia-in-motion-with-kaka/|title=new BRAVIA ad from Sony featuring Danny Dyer, with music by Kasabian and their new track Underdog|date=28 February 2009|work=[[Bravia (brand)|Bravia]]|accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Theme==\nThe [[Stanley Royd Hospital|West Riding Pauper Lunatic Asylum]] was a [[Psychiatric hospital|mental institution]] built in [[West Yorkshire]], England in 1818. [[Sergio Pizzorno]] further explained the choice of album title: \"The album isn't about the place, I just first heard about it on a TV documentary, and the words just struck me. I love the way it looked and the feeling it evokes. Apparently, it was one of the first loony bins for the poor, before that it was mainly rich people who got treatment.\"<ref name=\"NME-album-name\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/kasabian/45282|title=Kasabian reveal why they called album 'West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum'|date=12 June 2009|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|accessdate=13 June 2009}}</ref> The album cover depicts the band \"getting dressed up for a party at the [[Psychiatric hospital|asylum]], looking in the mirror at the costumes\". Inspiration for such cover originated from the artwork of [[Amon D\u00fc\u00fcl II]]'s album ''Made in Germany''.<ref name=\"NME-album-name\" /> In an interview with [[T4 (Channel 4)|T4]], the band said that each track is meant to represent an inmate within the asylum.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album reviews\n| MC = 68/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum/kasabian|title=Reviews for West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum by Kasabian|website=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum-mw0000818188|title=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum - Kasabian|last=Jeffries|first=David|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[Drowned in Sound]]\n| rev2Score = (5/10)<ref name=\"DiS\">{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/14441/reviews/4137049|title=Album Review: Kasabian - West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|last=Gourlay|first=Dom|website=[[Drowned in Sound]]|date=8 June 2009|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/jun/05/kasabian-pauper-lunatic-asylum|title=Pop review: Kasabian, West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|last=Simpson|first=Dave|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=5 June 2009|accessdate=27 August 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-kasabian-west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum-columbia-1697059.html|title=Album: Kasabian, West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum (Columbia)|last=Gill|first=Andy|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=23 October 2011|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = 8/10<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/kasabian/10518|title=Album review: Kasabian - 'West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum'|last=MacBain|first=Hamish|magazine=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|date=2 June 2009|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 4.9/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/13154-west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum/|title=Kasabian: West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|last=Cohen|first=Ian|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=8 June 2009|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3|10}}<ref name=\"PM\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/93480-kasabian-west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum/|title=Kasabian: West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|last=Stewart|first=Bill|magazine=[[PopMatters]]|date=9 June 2009|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite magazine|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/28488563/review/29546492/west_ryder_pauper_lunatic_asylum|title=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum : Kasabian : Review|last=Hoard|first=Christian|magazine=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|date=5 August 2009|accessdate=27 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090826162557/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/28488563/review/29546492/west_ryder_pauper_lunatic_asylum|archivedate=26 August 2009|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite magazine|url=http://spin.com/reviews/kasabian-west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum-rca|title=Kasabian, 'West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum' (RCA)|last=Bevan|first=David|magazine=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|date=20 May 2009|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Uncut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/album/kasabian-west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum|title=Kasabian - West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|last=Sweeting|first=Adam|work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|publisher=[[Time Inc. UK]]|date=2 June 2009|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n''West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum'' received positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critic]]s. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 68, based on 15 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\nAdam Sweeting of ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' praised the band for putting a lot more depth into their sound while delivering the songs with a dark undertone to them, calling it \"A world away from their ladrock roots, you might say.\"<ref name=\"Uncut\"/> Dave Simpson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' also gave praise to the band's newfound demented sound, noting that their trademark tracks are more melodic and utilize different instrumentals, concluding that \"the resulting epic is barmy and beautiful, suggesting that while Kasabian's amps go up to 11, they can also sound good when they're turned down to four.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Hamish MacBain of ''[[NME]]'' praised the album's mishmash of psychedelic-infused tracks resembling that of [[The Rolling Stones]]' ''[[Their Satanic Majesties Request]]'', calling it \"a shambling, splattered, ultimately much more enduring mess that will make sense if you just hang on in there.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/>\n\nAndrew Leahey of [[AllMusic]] commended the band for improving on their previous effort with a psychedelic sense and horror-like atmosphere mixed with their usual dance-rock sound, calling it \"an interesting, unexpected piece of work, devoid of a militantly commercial single like ''[[Empire (Kasabian album)|Empire]]''{{'}}s [[Empire (Kasabian song)|self-titled track]], and lacking the shaggy Madchester vibes that [[Christopher Karloff]] brought to 2004's ''[[Kasabian (album)|Kasabian]]''.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> While praising tracks like \"Fast Fuse\" and \"Ladies and Gentlemen (Roll the Dice)\" for deviating away from their [[Madchester]] sound into more '60s sounding bands like the Stones and [[T-Rex (band)|T-Rex]], Dom Gourlay of [[Drowned in Sound]] criticized the album for carrying half thought-out tracks with production that apes the sounds of other well-known Britpop bands, saying that it \"suffers in the most part for being so predictable.\"<ref name=\"DiS\"/> Bill Stewart of [[PopMatters]] felt the album was bogged down by the band's pretentious, instrumental choices and studio handling, saying that \"All the gimmicky studio effects in the world can't mask the fact that this album is likely to be one of the most hollow you'll hear all year.\"<ref name=\"PM\"/>\n\n==Singles and videos==\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2009}}\n* \"[[Fast Fuse]]\" \u2013 Released on 2 October 2007 as a [[bootleg recording|bootleg]] single. Although not being the first official single from the album it was the first material released from it, receiving airplay on [[Xfm]], [[Absolute Radio]] and being posted on YouTube. Members of Kasabian's fan club at the time could buy the song on a one sided [[Gramophone record|10\"]]. Despite receiving some airplay and a limited release it never had a video. It was also used on the video game ''[[FIFA 09]]''. As well as this, the song was used as the theme tune for ''[[Russell Howard's Good News]]'', broadcast on [[BBC Two]] (previously [[BBC Three]]) in the UK.\n* \"Vlad the Impaler\" \u2013 Released as a free single on 31 March 2009 to 3 April 2009. The song only got minor airplay. The song was released with a video featuring [[Noel Fielding]] as Vlad. The video was directed by [[Richard Ayoade]]. Later released on 14 February 2010 with a second music video to accompany it as the fourth official single.\n* \"[[Fire (Kasabian song)|Fire]]\" \u2013 Released as the first official single on 1 June and reached number 3 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n* \"[[Underdog (Kasabian song)|Underdog]]\" \u2013 Released on 26 October 2009 and reached number 32 in the UK Singles Chart.\n* \"[[Where Did All the Love Go?]]\" \u2013 Released on 17 August 2009, the song was the third official single charting at 30 in the UK charts. A music video has been released to support the single.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| all_writing     = Sergio Pizzorno, except where noted\n| title1          = [[Underdog (Kasabian song)|Underdog]]\n| length1         = 4:37\n| title2          = [[Where Did All the Love Go?]]\n| length2         = 4:17\n| title3          = Swarfiga\n| length3         = 2:18\n| title4          = [[Fast Fuse]]\n| length4         = 4:10\n| title5          = Take Aim\n| length5         = 5:23\n| title6          = Thick as Thieves\n| length6         = 3:06\n| title7          = West Ryder Silver Bullet\n| length7         = 5:15\n| title