        = Live from the Little Noise Sessions\n| title6          = Runaway\n| length6         = 3:45\n| note6           = Live from the Little Noise Sessions\n| title7          = Thick as Thieves\n| length7         = 3:26\n| note7           = Live from the Royal Albert Hall for Teenage Cancer Trust\n| title8          = Fast Fuse\n| length8         = 4:06\n| note8           = Live from the Royal Albert Hall for Teenage Cancer Trust\n| title9          = Club Foot\n| length9         = 4:44\n| note9           = Live from the Royal Albert Hall for Teenage Cancer Trust\n| title10         = L.S.F. (Lost Souls Forever)\n| length10        = 7:21\n| note10          = Live from the Royal Albert Hall for Teenage Cancer Trust\n| title11         = Vlad the Impaler\n| length11        =\n| note11          = Video\n| title12         = Vlad the Impaler\n| length12        =\n| note12          = Making of\n| title13         = Fire\n| length13        =\n| note13          = Music Film\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Australian Tour Edition Bonus Tracks\n| collapsed = yes\n| title13         = Julie & The Moth Man\n| length13        =\n| title14         = Where Did All the Love Go?\n| length14        =\n| note14          = Burns Remix\n| title15         = Vlad the Impaler\n| length15        =\n| note15          = Zane Lowe Remix\n| title16         = Take Aim\n| length16        =\n| note16          = Dan the Automator Remix\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline        = Australian Tour Edition Bonus DVD\n| collapsed = yes\n| title1          = Underdog\n| length1         =\n| note1           = Live at T4\n| title2          = Where Did All the Love Go?\n| length2         =\n| note2           = Live at T4\n| title3          = Thick as Thieves\n| length3         =\n| note3           = Live at T4\n| title4          = Fire\n| length4         =\n| note4           = Live at T4\n| title5          = Club Foot\n| length5         =\n| note5           = Live at T4\n| title6          = Empire\n| length6         =\n| note6           = Live at T4\n| title7          = Vlad the Impaler\n| length7         =\n| note7           = Video\n| title8          = Underdog\n| length8         =\n| note8           = Video \u2013 International Version\n| title9          = Fire\n| length9         =\n| note9           = Video\n| title10         = Where Did All the Love Go?\n| length10        =\n| note10          = Video\n| title11         = Underdog\n| length11        =\n| note11          = Video \u2013 UK Version\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n;Kasabian\n*[[Tom Meighan]] \u2013 lead vocals (all tracks except \"Swarfiga\", \"Take Aim\", \"Secret Alphabets\" and \"Happiness\")\n*[[Sergio Pizzorno]] \u2013 lead and rhythm guitar, synths, programming, backing vocals, lead vocals on \"Take Aim\", \"Secret Alphabets\" and \"Happiness\"\n*[[Chris Edwards (musician)|Chris Edwards]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Ian Matthews (drummer)|Ian Matthews]] \u2013 drums\n\n;Additional personnel\n*[[Dan the Automator]] \u2013 additional programming\n*[[Jay Mehler]] \u2013 additional guitar on \"Underdog\", \"Ladies and Gentlemen (Roll the Dice)\" and \"Happiness\"\n*Tim Carter \u2013 additional guitar, keyboards and percussion\n*Daniel Ralph Martin \u2013 additional guitar on \"Fast Fuse\" and piano on \"Happiness\"\n*[[Rosario Dawson]] \u2013 co-lead vocals on \"West Ryder Silver Bullet\"\n*[[Ben Kealey]] \u2013 additional keyboards on \"Ladies and Gentlemen (Roll the Dice)\"\n*Rosie Danvers \u2013 strings direction\n*Wired Strings \u2013 strings on \"Where Did All the Love Go?\", \"Take Aim\", \"West Ryder Silver Bullet\" e \"Secret Alphabets\"\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2009)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Australia|11|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Austria|56|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Netherlands|85|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|France|30|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n|Irish Albums ([[Irish Albums Chart|IRMA]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|Japanese Albums [[Oricon|Japan Albums Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n{{albumchart|New Zealand|23|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Switzerland|27|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|UK|1|artist=Kasabian}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|126|artist=Kasabian}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|BillboardIndependent|26|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 September 2014}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|BillboardRock|49|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 September 2014}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United Kingdom|artist=Kasabian|title=Empire|award=Platinum|number=2|certyear=2009|relyear=2010|salesamount=803,000|salesref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/kasabians-official-top-10-biggest-singles-revealed__18747/|title=Kasabian's Official Top 10 biggest singles revealed|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=3 May 2017|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Kasabian}}\n\n[[Category:Kasabian albums]]\n[[Category:2009 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dan the Automator]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2013}}\n{{EngvarB|date=September 2013}}\n{{More citations needed|date=August 2013}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Kasabian]]\n| cover      = Westryderpauperlunaticasylum.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = 5 June 2009\n| recorded   = {{plainlist|\n* Orangutan Studios ([[Greensboro, North Carolina]])\n* E-Land Mig Studios ([[Earl Shilton, Leicestershire]])\n* Lookout Studios ([[San Francisco, California]])\n}}\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Indie rock]]<ref name=\"Clash\">{{cite web|url=http://www.clashmusic.com/news/kasabian-planning-special-festival-slots|title=Kasabian Planning Special Festival Slots|work=[[Clash Magazine|Clash]]''|accessdate=12 March 2011}}</ref>\n* [[psychedelic rock]]<ref name =\"NME\"/>\n* [[space rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2011/09/album-review-kasabian-velociraptor/|title= Kasabian - Velociraptor!|website=[[Consequence of Sound]]|accessdate=December 29, 2015}}</ref>\n* [[experimental rock]]<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.gigwise.com/reviews/51157/kasabian---west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum-sony-080609|title=KASABIAN - 'WEST RYDER PAUPER LUNATIC ASYLUM' (SONY) 08/06/09|website=[[Gigwise]]|accessdate=December 29, 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n| length     = 51:59\n| label      = {{flatlist|\n* [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n* [[Kasabian|Paradise]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Dan the Automator]]\n* [[Sergio Pizzorno]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Empire (Kasabian album)|Empire]]\n| prev_year  = 2006\n| next_title = [[Velociraptor!]]\n| next_year  = 2011\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum\n | type        = studio\n | single1     = [[Fire (Kasabian song)|Fire]]\n | single1date = 1 June 2009\n | single2     = [[Where Did All the Love Go?]]\n | single2date = 17 August 2009\n | single3     = [[Underdog (Kasabian song)|Underdog]]\n | single3date = 26 October 2009\n | single4     = [[Vlad the Impaler (song)|Vlad the Impaler]]\n | single4date = 14 February 2010\n}}\n}}\n'''''West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum''''' is the third studio album by British [[indie rock]]<ref name=\"Clash\"/> band [[Kasabian]], which was released on 5 June 2009. It is also the first album by the band to not feature [[Christopher Karloff]], the band's lead guitarist and songwriter, following his departure during the writing stages of Kasabian's second album, ''[[Empire (Kasabian album)|Empire]]'' (2006). The rhythm guitarist [[Sergio Pizzorno]] took over as the main force behind the band's songwriting.\n\nThe album was nominated for the 2009 [[Mercury Prize]]. In October 2009, it was voted the best album of the year by [[Q (magazine)|''Q'' Magazine]].\n\n==History==\n\"Vlad the Impaler\" was made available as a free download from the official website from 31 March to 3 April 2009. The first proper, physical release from the album was \"[[Fire (Kasabian song)|Fire]]\", which was released on 1 June.<ref>[http://blog.kasabian.co.uk/post/89685282/vlad-the-impaler-free-download]  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090525030141/http://blog.kasabian.co.uk/post/89685282/vlad-the-impaler-free-download |date=25 May 2009 }}</ref> [[Sergio Pizzorno]] has called the 52-minute album \"the soundtrack to an imaginary movie.\" The album includes a duet, on the track \"West Ryder Silver Bullet\", with the actress [[Rosario Dawson]]. The album entered the [[UK Album Chart]] at No. 1, giving the band their second No. 1 album.\n\"Underdog\" has been used by [[Sony]] in a commercial for their [[BRAVIA]] Televisions.<ref name=\"Bravia-commercial\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvadmusic.co.uk/2009/02/sony-bravia-in-motion-with-kaka/|title=new BRAVIA ad from Sony featuring Danny Dyer, with music by Kasabian and their new track Underdog|date=28 February 2009|work=[[Bravia (brand)|Bravia]]|accessdate=15 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Theme==\nThe [[Stanley Royd Hospital|West Riding Pauper Lunatic Asylum]] was a [[Psychiatric hospital|mental institution]] built in [[West Yorkshire]], England in 1818. [[Sergio Pizzorno]] further explained the choice of album title: \"The album isn't about the place, I just first heard about it on a TV documentary, and the words just struck me. I love the way it looked and the feeling it evokes. Apparently, it was one of the first loony bins for the poor, before that it was mainly rich people who got treatment.\"<ref name=\"NME-album-name\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/kasabian/45282|title=Kasabian reveal why they called album 'West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum'|date=12 June 2009|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|accessdate=13 June 2009}}</ref> The album cover depicts the band \"getting dressed up for a party at the [[Psychiatric hospital|asylum]], looking in the mirror at the costumes\". Inspiration for such cover originated from the artwork of [[Amon D\u00fc\u00fcl II]]'s album ''Made in Germany''.<ref name=\"NME-album-name\" /> In an interview with [[T4 (Channel 4)|T4]], the band said that each track is meant to represent an inmate within the asylum.\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album reviews\n| MC = 68/100<ref name=\"Metacritic\">{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum/kasabian|title=Reviews for West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum by Kasabian|work=[[Metacritic]]|publisher=[[CBS Interactive]]|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"AM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum-mw0000818188|title=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum - Kasabian|last=Jeffries|first=David|website=[[AllMusic]]|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev2 = [[Drowned in Sound]]\n| rev2Score = (5/10)<ref name=\"DiS\">{{cite web|url=http://drownedinsound.com/releases/14441/reviews/4137049|title=Album Review: Kasabian - West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|last=Gourlay|first=Dom|website=[[Drowned in Sound]]|date=8 June 2009|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev3Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2009/jun/05/kasabian-pauper-lunatic-asylum|title=Pop review: Kasabian, West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|last=Simpson|first=Dave|work=[[The Guardian]]|publisher=[[Guardian Media Group]]|date=5 June 2009|accessdate=27 August 2011|location=London}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev4Score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"Independent\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/album-kasabian-west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum-columbia-1697059.html|title=Album: Kasabian, West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum (Columbia)|last=Gill|first=Andy|work=[[The Independent]]|publisher=Independent Print Limited|date=23 October 2011|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev5Score = 8/10<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/reviews/kasabian/10518|title=Album review: Kasabian - 'West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum'|last=MacBain|first=Hamish|work=[[NME]]|publisher=[[IPC Media]]|date=2 June 2009|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev6Score = 4.9/10<ref name=\"Pitchfork\">{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/13154-west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum/|title=Kasabian: West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|last=Cohen|first=Ian|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|date=8 June 2009|accessdate=27 August 2011}}</ref>\n| rev7 = ''[[PopMatters]]''\n| rev7Score = {{Rating|3|10}}<ref name=\"PM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.popmatters.com/review/93480-kasabian-west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum/|title=Kasabian: West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|last=Stewart|first=Bill|work=[[PopMatters]]|date=9 June 2009|accessdate=11 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev8 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev8Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/28488563/review/29546492/west_ryder_pauper_lunatic_asylum|title=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum : Kasabian : Review|last=Hoard|first=Christian|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|publisher=[[Jann Wenner|Wenner Media]]|date=5 August 2009|accessdate=27 August 2011|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090826162557/http://www.rollingstone.com/reviews/album/28488563/review/29546492/west_ryder_pauper_lunatic_asylum|archivedate=26 August 2009}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]''\n| rev9Score = {{Rating|2.5|5}}<ref name=\"Spin\">{{cite web|url=http://spin.com/reviews/kasabian-west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum-rca|title=Kasabian, 'West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum' (RCA)|last=Bevan|first=David|work=[[Spin (magazine)|Spin]]|publisher=[[SpinMedia]]|date=20 May 2009|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| rev10Score = {{Rating|5|5}}<ref name=\"Uncut\">{{cite web|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/reviews/album/kasabian-west-ryder-pauper-lunatic-asylum|title=Kasabian - West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|last=Sweeting|first=Adam|work=[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]|publisher=[[Time Inc. UK]]|date=2 June 2009|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref>\n}}\n''West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum'' received positive reviews from [[Music journalism|music critic]]s. At [[Metacritic]], which assigns a [[Standard score|normalized]] rating out of 100 to reviews from mainstream critics, the album received an [[Weighted mean|average]] score of 68, based on 15 reviews.<ref name=\"Metacritic\"/>\n\nAdam Sweeting of ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' praised the band for putting a lot more depth into their sound while delivering the songs with a dark undertone to them, calling it \"A world away from their ladrock roots, you might say.\"<ref name=\"Uncut\"/> Dave Simpson of ''[[The Guardian]]'' also gave praise to the band's newfound demented sound, noting that their trademark tracks are more melodic and utilize different instrumentals, concluding that \"the resulting epic is barmy and beautiful, suggesting that while Kasabian's amps go up to 11, they can also sound good when they're turned down to four.\"<ref name=\"Guardian\"/> Hamish MacBain of ''[[NME]]'' praised the album's mishmash of psychedelic-infused tracks resembling that of [[The Rolling Stones]]' ''[[Their Satanic Majesties Request]]'', calling it \"a shambling, splattered, ultimately much more enduring mess that will make sense if you just hang on in there.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/>\n\nAndrew Leahey of [[AllMusic]] commended the band for improving on their previous effort with a psychedelic sense and horror-like atmosphere mixed with their usual dance-rock sound, calling it \"an interesting, unexpected piece of work, devoid of a militantly commercial single like ''[[Empire (Kasabian album)|Empire]]''{{'}}s [[Empire (Kasabian song)|self-titled track]], and lacking the shaggy Madchester vibes that [[Christopher Karloff]] brought to 2004's ''[[Kasabian (album)|Kasabian]]''.\"<ref name=\"AM\"/> While praising tracks like \"Fast Fuse\" and \"Ladies and Gentlemen (Roll the Dice)\" for deviating away from their [[Madchester]] sound into more '60s sounding bands like the Stones and [[T-Rex (band)|T-Rex]], Dom Gourlay of [[Drowned in Sound]] criticized the album for carrying half thought-out tracks with production that apes the sounds of other well-known Britpop bands, saying that it \"suffers in the most part for being so predictable.\"<ref name=\"DiS\"/> Bill Stewart of [[PopMatters]] felt the album was bogged down by the band's pretentious, instrumental choices and studio handling, saying that \"All the gimmicky studio effects in the world can't mask the fact that this album is likely to be one of the most hollow you'll hear all year.\"<ref name=\"PM\"/>\n\n==Singles and videos==\n{{unreferenced section|date=July 2009}}\n* \"[[Fast Fuse]]\" \u2013 Released on 2 October 2007 as a [[bootleg recording|bootleg]] single. Although not being the first official single from the album it was the first material released from it, receiving airplay on [[Xfm]], [[Absolute Radio]] and being posted on YouTube. Members of Kasabian's fan club at the time could buy the song on a one sided [[Gramophone record|10\"]]. Despite receiving some airplay and a limited release it never had a video. It was also used on the video game ''[[FIFA 09]]''. As well as this, the song was used as the theme tune for ''[[Russell Howard's Good News]]'', broadcast on [[BBC Two]] (previously [[BBC Three]]) in the UK.\n* \"Vlad the Impaler\" \u2013 Released as a free single on 31 March 2009 to 3 April 2009. The song only got minor airplay. The song was released with a video featuring [[Noel Fielding]] as Vlad. The video was directed by [[Richard Ayoade]]. Later released on 14 February 2010 with a second music video to accompany it as the fourth official single.\n* \"[[Fire (Kasabian song)|Fire]]\" \u2013 Released as the first official single on 1 June and reached number 3 on the [[UK Singles Chart]].\n* \"[[Underdog (Kasabian song)|Underdog]]\" \u2013 Released on 26 October 2009 and reached number 32 in the UK Singles Chart.\n* \"[[Where Did All the Love Go?]]\" \u2013 Released on 17 August 2009, the song was the third official single charting at 30 in the UK charts. A music video has been released to support the single.\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n| all_writing     = Sergio Pizzorno, except where noted\n| title1          = [[Underdog (Kasabian song)|Underdog]]\n| length1         = 4:37\n| title2          = [[Where Did All the Love Go?]]\n| length2         = 4:17\n| title3          = Swarfiga\n| length3         = 2:18\n| title4          = [[Fast Fuse]]\n| length4         = 4:10\n| title5          = Take Aim\n| length5         = 5:23\n| title6          = Thick as Thieves\n| length6         = 3:06\n| title7          = West Ryder Silver Bullet\n| length7         = 5:15\n| title8          = Vlad the Impaler\n| length8         = 4:44\n| title9          = Ladies and Gentlemen, Roll the Dice\n| length9         = 3:33\n| title10         = Secret Alphabets\n| note10 = Pizzorno, Helmut Zacharias\n| length10        = 5:07\n| title11         = [[Fire (Kasabian song)|Fire]]\n| length11        = 4:13\n| title12         = Happiness\n| length12        = 5:16\n}}\n\n{{tracklist\n| headline = Japan Only Bonus Tracks\n| collapsed = yes\n| title13         = [[Runaway (Del Shannon song)|Runaway]]\n| note13      