sabian\n*[[Tom Meighan]] \u2013 lead vocals (all tracks except \"Swarfiga\", \"Take Aim\", \"Secret Alphabets\" and \"Happiness\")\n*[[Sergio Pizzorno]] \u2013 lead and rhythm guitar, synths, programming, backing vocals, lead vocals on \"Take Aim\", \"Secret Alphabets\" and \"Happiness\"\n*[[Chris Edwards (musician)|Chris Edwards]] \u2013 bass guitar\n*[[Ian Matthews (drummer)|Ian Matthews]] \u2013 drums\n\n;Additional personnel\n*[[Dan the Automator]] \u2013 additional programming\n*[[Jay Mehler]] \u2013 additional guitar on \"Underdog\", \"Ladies and Gentlemen (Roll the Dice)\" and \"Happiness\"\n*Tim Carter \u2013 additional guitar, keyboards and percussion\n*Daniel Ralph Martin \u2013 additional guitar on \"Fast Fuse\" and piano on \"Happiness\"\n*[[Rosario Dawson]] \u2013 co-lead vocals on \"West Ryder Silver Bullet\"\n*[[Ben Kealey]] \u2013 additional keyboards on \"Ladies and Gentlemen (Roll the Dice)\"\n*Rosie Danvers \u2013 strings direction\n*Wired Strings \u2013 strings on \"Where Did All the Love Go?\", \"Take Aim\", \"West Ryder Silver Bullet\" e \"Secret Alphabets\"\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Chart (2009)\n! Peak<br />position\n|-\n{{albumchart|Australia|11|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Austria|56|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Netherlands|85|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|France|30|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n|Irish Albums ([[Irish Albums Chart|IRMA]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|4\n|-\n|Japanese Albums [[Oricon|Japan Albums Chart]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n{{albumchart|New Zealand|23|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Switzerland|27|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|UK|1|artist=Kasabian}}\n|-\n{{albumchart|Billboard200|126|artist=Kasabian}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|BillboardIndependent|26|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 September 2014}}\n|-\n|{{albumchart|BillboardRock|49|artist=Kasabian|album=West Ryder Pauper Lunatic Asylum|rowheader=true|accessdate=19 September 2014}}\n|}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|type=album|region=United Kingdom|artist=Kasabian|title=Empire|award=Platinum|number=2|certyear=2009|relyear=2010|salesamount=803,000|salesref=<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/kasabians-official-top-10-biggest-singles-revealed__18747/|title=Kasabian's Official Top 10 biggest singles revealed|last=Copsey|first=Rob|date=3 May 2017|website=[[Official Charts Company]]|access-date=3 May 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n{{Kasabian}}\n\n[[Category:Kasabian albums]]\n[[Category:2009 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Dan the Automator]]\n", "name_user": "DepressedPer", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCritical reception:C/E.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/West_Ryder_Pauper_Lunatic_Asylum"}
{"title_page": "Ellis Price", "text_new": "{{short description|Welsh administrator and politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n'''Ellis Price''' or '''Prys''' (by 1514-8 October 1594) was a Welsh administrator and MP.\n\nHe was a younger son of Robert ap Rhys of [[Pentrefoelas|Plas Iolyn]], the chaplain to [[Cardinal Wolsey]]. His grandfather [[Rhys Fawr ap Maredudd]] had fought at [[Battle of Bosworth Field|Bosworth]] with [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]].\n\nEllis studied at St Nicholas Hostel, Cambridge and was awarded BCL in 1533 and DCL in 1534 and from the red gown of his degree was known as \u2018Y Doctor Coch\u2019 (\u2018The Red Doctor\u2019).<ref name = NLW>{{cite web|url = http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-PRYS-ELI-1512.html| title= PRYS (PRICE), ELIS (1512? - 1594?) \u2018Y Doctor Coch\u2019 (\u2018The Red Doctor\u2019), of Plas Iolyn| publisher= The National Library of Wales|accessdate = 18 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\">{{cite web|title=PRICE, Ellis (by 1514-94), of Plas Iolyn and Ysbyty Ifan, Denb.|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/price-ellis-1514-94|website=The History of Parliament - Members Biographies}}</ref>\n\nIn 1535 he was appointed visitor of monasteries in Wales by [[Thomas Cromwell]] and played a leading role in their subsequent destruction. There were complaints about his immorality and arrogance and he was dismissed.<ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\"/> In 1538 he became chancellor and commissary-general of the [[Diocese of St Asaph]] and sinecure rector of [[Llangwm, Conwy|Llangwm]], [[Llandrillo-yn-Rhos]] and [[Llanuwchllyn]].<ref name = NLW/> At about this time he was sued in [[Court of Chancery|Chancery]] by the vicar of Llanarmon, Denbighshire, who complained that Price aided and abetted in the misappropriation of tithes; he also took part in an assault upon the Welsh scholar and translator of the [[New Testament]] into Welsh,<ref name=Cathrall>{{cite book|last1=Cathrall|first1=William|title=The History of North Wales|date=1828|publisher=J. Gleave and sons|page=189|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oUpNAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA189&lpg=PA189&dq=William+Salesbury+of+Llanrwst&source=bl&ots=4GhLiDB2Ys&sig=MYCzSvCnhBvJYXSEEfSKg2FjIeU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Xs40VbrbHMvSaMXGgbAF&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=William%20Salesbury%20of%20Llanrwst&f=false}}</ref> [[William Salesbury]] of Llanrwst, Denbighshire, who was his brother-in-law.<ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\"/>\n\nHe was a [[Justice of the Peace]] for Merioneth in 1543 and from 1555 to his death, for Denbighshire from 1555 to his death, for Caernarvonshire from 1561 to his death, for Anglesey and Montgomeryshire in 1564, and for most Welsh counties by 1575. He was appointed [[High Sheriff of Denbighshire]] for 1548\u201349, 1556\u201357, 1568\u201369 and 1572\u201373 and [[High Sheriff of Merionethshire]] for 1551\u201352, 1555\u201356, 1563\u201364, 1567\u201368, 1573\u201374, 1578\u201379 and 1583\u201384. In the intervening years he also served as [[High Sheriff of Caernarvonshire]] (1558\u201359) and [[High Sheriff of Anglesey]] (1577\u201378 and 1585\u201386).<ref name = NLW/><ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\"/>\n\nHe was elected MP for [[Merioneth (UK Parliament constituency)|Merioneth]] in 1558 and 1563.<ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\"/> Other offices included [[Custos Rotulorum of Merionethshire]] from 1558/59 to 1577 or later, member of the [[Council in the Marches of Wales]] from 1560 to his death, and [[Master in Chancery|Master in Chancery extraordinary]].<ref name = NLW/>\n\nIn 1560, the Crown awarded him the manor of Tir Ifan, with lands at [[Ysbyty Ifan]] and [[Penmachno]]. When Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]] gave the lordship of Denbigh as a gift to [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester]] in 1564, Price, as steward of the estates, carried out acts of oppression in the area. He was on the commission granted by Elizabeth to hold the [[Eisteddfod]] at [[Caerwys]] in 1567.<ref name = NLW/>\n\nHe married twice: firstly to Catherine, the daughter of Thomas Conway of Bodrhyddan, Flintshire, who bore him a son; and secondly to Ellyw, the daughter of Owain Pool, rector of [[Llandecwyn]], Merioneth, who delivered two further sons and four daughters. His eldest son was the adventurer poet [[Tomos Prys]].<ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Price, Ellis}}\n[[Category:People from Denbighshire]]\n[[Category:1594 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of England (pre-1707) for constituencies in Wales]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Denbighshire]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Merionethshire]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Anglesey]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Caernarvonshire]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1558]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1563\u20131567]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Welsh administrator and politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=February 2018}}\n'''Ellis Price''' or '''Prys''' (by 1514-8 October 1594) was a Welsh administrator and MP.\n\nHe was a younger son of Robert ap Rhys of [[Pentrefoelas|Plas Iolyn]], the chaplain to [[Cardinal Wolsey]]. His grandfather [[Rhys Fawr ap Maredudd]] had fought at [[Battle of Bosworth Field|Bosworth]] with [[Henry VII of England|Henry VII]].\n\nEllis studied at St Nicholas Hostel, Cambridge and was awarded BCL in 1533 and DCL in 1534 and from the red gown of his degree was known as \u2018Y Doctor Coch\u2019 (\u2018The Red Doctor\u2019).<ref name = NLW>{{cite web|url = http://wbo.llgc.org.uk/en/s-PRYS-ELI-1512.html| title= PRYS (PRICE), ELIS (1512? - 1594?) \u2018Y Doctor Coch\u2019 (\u2018The Red Doctor\u2019), of Plas Iolyn| publisher= The National Library of Wales|accessdate = 18 July 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\">{{cite web|title=PRICE, Ellis (by 1514-94), of Plas Iolyn and Ysbyty Ifan, Denb.|url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1509-1558/member/price-ellis-1514-94|website=The History of Parliament - Members Biographies}}</ref>\n\nIn 1535 he was appointed visitor of monasteries in Wales by [[Thomas Cromwell]] and played a leading role in their subsequent destruction. There were complaints about his immorality and arrogance and he was dismissed.<ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\"/> In 1538 he became chancellor and commissary-general of the [[Diocese of St Asaph]] and sinecure rector of [[Llangwm, Conwy|Llangwm]], [[Llandrillo-yn-Rhos]] and [[Llanuwchllyn]].<ref name = NLW/> At about this time he was sued in [[Court of Chancery|Chancery]] by the vicar of Llanarmon, Denbighshire, who complained that Price aided and abetted in the misappropriation of tithes; he also took part in an assault upon the Welsh scholar and translator of the [[New Testament]] into Welsh,<ref name=Cathrall>{{cite book|last1=Cathrall|first1=William|title=The History of North Wales|date=1828|publisher=J. Gleave and sons|page=189|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=oUpNAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA189&lpg=PA189&dq=William+Salesbury+of+Llanrwst&source=bl&ots=4GhLiDB2Ys&sig=MYCzSvCnhBvJYXSEEfSKg2FjIeU&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Xs40VbrbHMvSaMXGgbAF&ved=0CE8Q6AEwCA#v=onepage&q=William%20Salesbury%20of%20Llanrwst&f=false}}</ref> [[William Salesbury]] of Llanrwst, Denbighshire, who was his brother-in-law.<ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\"/>\n\nHe was a [[Justice of the Peace]] for Merioneth in 1543 and from 1555 to his death, for Denbighshire from 1555 to his death, for Caernarvonshire from 1561 to his death, for Anglesey and Montgomeryshire in 1564, and for most Welsh counties by 1575. He was appointed [[High Sheriff of Denbighshire]] for 1548-49, 1556\u201357, 1568\u201369 and 1572\u201373 and [[High Sheriff of Merionethshire]] for 1551-52, 1555\u201356, 1563\u201364, 1567\u201368, 1573\u201374, 1578\u201379 and 1583-84. In the intervening years he also served as [[High Sheriff of Caernarvonshire]] (1558\u201359) and [[High Sheriff of Anglesey]] (1577\u201378 and 1585\u201386).<ref name = NLW/><ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\"/>\n\nHe was elected MP for [[Merioneth (UK Parliament constituency)|Merioneth]] in 1558 and 1563.<ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\"/> Other offices included [[Custos Rotulorum of Merionethshire]] from 1558/59 to 1577 or later, member of the [[Council in the Marches of Wales]] from 1560 to his death, and [[Master in Chancery|Master in Chancery extraordinary]].<ref name = NLW/>\n\nIn 1560, the Crown awarded him the manor of Tir Ifan, with lands at [[Ysbyty Ifan]] and [[Penmachno]]. When Queen [[Elizabeth I of England|Elizabeth]] gave the lordship of Denbigh as a gift to [[Robert Dudley, 1st Earl of Leicester]] in 1564, Price, as steward of the estates, carried out acts of oppression in the area. He was on the commission granted by Elizabeth to hold the [[Eisteddfod]] at [[Caerwys]] in 1567.<ref name = NLW/>\n\nHe married twice: firstly to Catherine, the daughter of Thomas Conway of Bodrhyddan, Flintshire, who bore him a son; and secondly to Ellyw, the daughter of Owain Pool, rector of [[Llandecwyn]], Merioneth, who delivered two further sons and four daughters. His eldest son was the adventurer poet [[Tomos Prys]].<ref name=\"Hist of Parl Bio\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Price, Ellis}}\n[[Category:People from Denbighshire]]\n[[Category:1594 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of England (pre-1707) for constituencies in Wales]]\n[[Category:People of the Tudor period]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Denbighshire]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Merionethshire]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Anglesey]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Caernarvonshire]]\n[[Category:Year of birth uncertain]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1558]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1563\u20131567]]\n", "name_user": "J947", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:clean up,typo(s) fixed: 1548-49 \u2192 1548\u201349 (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ellis_Price"}
{"title_page": "Samaj Ko Badal Dalo (1947 film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Samaj Ko Badal Dalo\n| image          = Samaj_Ko_Badal_Dalo_(1947).jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Vijay Bhatt]]\n| producer       = Vijay Bhatt\n| writer         = Pandit Girish \n| story          = Pandit Girish\n| based on       = \n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Arun Kumar Ahuja|Arun Ahuja]]<br />Mridula<br />[[Yakub (actor)|Yakub]]<br />Leela Pawar\n| music          = [[Khemchand Prakash]]\n| cinematography = Yusuf Mulji\n| editing        = Pratap Dave\n| distributor    = \n| released       = 1947\n| runtime        = 133 min\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n| website        = \n}}\n'''''Samaj Ko Badal Dalo''''' (Change This World) is a [[List of Bollywood films of 1947|1947]] [[Cinema of India|Indian]] [[Hindi]] social melodrama film directed by [[Vijay Bhatt]]. Produced under the Prakash Pictures banner,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gomolo.com/samaj-ko-badal-dalo-movie-cast-crew/1643|title=Samaj Ko Badal Dalo (1947)|publisher=Gomolo.com|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref> its music composer was [[Khemchand Prakash]], with lyrics by Pandit Indra, Roopdas, and [[Qamar Jalalabadi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myswar.com/album/samaaj-ko-badal-dalo-1947 |title=Album-Samaj Ko Badal Dalo (1947)|publisher=MySwar|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref> The story, screenplay and dialogues were by Pandit Girish. Its cinematographer was Yusuf Mulji and the film starred [[Arun Kumar Ahuja|Arun Ahuja]], Mridula, [[Yakub (actor)|Yakub]], Leela Pawar, Umakant and Bikram Kapoor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citwf.com/film303846.htm|title=Samaj Ko Badal Dalo |publisher=Alan Goble|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nBhatt's social film dealt with the issue of \"mismatched\" marriages and advocated divorce, setting a partner free in order to choose their own mate.<ref name=\"Congress2007\">{{cite book|author=Indian History Congress|title=Proceedings - Indian History Congress|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GhVDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=18 January 2015|year=2007}}</ref> ''[[Samaj Ko Badal Dalo]]'' (1970) is a film of the same name directed by [[V. Madhusudan Rao]] and produced by [[Gemini Studios|Gemini]], however it had no relation to the 1947 film,<ref name=\"RajadhyakshaWillemen2014\">{{cite book|author1=Ashish Rajadhyaksha|author2=Paul Willemen|author3=Professor of Critical Studies Paul Willemen|title=Encyclopedia of Indian Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SLkABAAAQBAJ&pg=PT67|accessdate=18 January 2015|date=10 July 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-94318-9|pages=67\u2013}}</ref> but was instead a remake of [[A. Vincent]]'s award-winning [[Malayalam]] film, ''[[Thulabharam]]'' (1968)<ref name=\"Shankar\">{{cite book|title=Shankar's weekly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FLQcAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=18 January 2015|year=1970}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nKishore ([[Arun Kumar Ahuja|Arun]]) and Manorama (Mridula) are in love, but unable to get married. Mridula's father is a clerk, who can't afford to pay the dowry demanded by Arun's family. Jayant ([[Yakub (actor)|Yakub]]) is a widower, and Mridula is married off to him. His cruel behaviour becomes apparent when he starts torturing Mridula soon after their marriage. Arun's parents get him married to the rich Champa (Leela Pawar), who is in love with someone else. Arun helps her marry Naresh, the man she loves, by giving her a divorce. Arun watches the torture inflicted on Mridula and the story then continues through tense scenes where eventually Arun kills Jayant and unwittingly Mridula, too, following which he's sent to a mental asylum having been declared insane.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Arun Kumar Ahuja|Arun]] as Kishore\n* Mridula Rani as Manorama\n* [[Yakub (actor)|Yakub]] as Jayant\n* Leela Pawar as Champa \n* Umakant\n* Bikram Kapoor\n* Prem Dhawan\n* Ramesh Sinha\n* Shabnam\n* Mohammed Rafi\n\n==Crew==\nThe film's crew consisted of:\n* Directed: [[Vijay Bhatt]]\n* Produced: Vijay Bhatt \n* Story: Pandit Girish\n* Screenplay: Pandit Girish\n* Dialogue: Pandit Girish\n* Cinematography: Yusuf Mulji\n* Choreography:\tSachin Shankar, Sharad Shukla\n* Editing: Pratap Dave\n* Art Direction: M. V. Dubashe, B. M. Shukla\n* Audiography: T. K. Dave\n* Music: [[Khemchand Prakash]]\n* Lyrics: Pandit Indra, Roopdas, [[Qamar Jalalabadi]]\n\n==Soundtrack==\n''Samaj Ko Badal Dalo'' was one of the early films for which [[Mohammed Rafi]] recorded songs in [[Bombay]]. The others were ''[[Gaon Ki Gori]]'' (1946) and ''[[Jugnu (1947 film)|Jugnu]]'' (1947).<ref name=\"Brittanica, India\">{{cite book|title=Students' Britannica India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ISFBJarYX7YC&pg=PA238|accessdate=18 January 2015|year=2000|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-0-85229-760-5|pages=238\u2013}}</ref> The music direction was by [[Khemchand Prakash]], with lyrics by Pandit Indra, Roopdas and [[Qamar Jalabadi]]. The playback singers were [[Mohammed Rafi]], [[Manna Dey]], [[Arun Kumar Ahuja]] and [[Amirbai Karnataki]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://muvyz.com/moviepage/ao993709/songs/#tabs|title=Songs Samaj Ko Badal Dalo (1947)|publisher=Muvyz, Inc|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Song List===\n{| border=\"4\" cellpadding=\"7\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#cccccc\"\n! # !! Title !!Singer !! Lyricist \n|- \n| 1\n| \"Aye Ji Mat Pucho Kuch Baat\"\n| Mohammed Rafi, Manna Dey, Arun Kumar\n| Pandit Indra\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Dhire Dhire Chale Aao\"\n| \n|Pandit Indra\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Tu Kyun Yaad Aata Hai Yaad Aane Wale\"\n| \n| Qamar Jalalabadi\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Naina Ro Ro Ke Rah Gaye\"\n| [[Amirbai Karnataki]]\n| Roopdas\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Tori Unchi Atariya Pe Aaun Kaise\"\n|Zohrabai Ambalewali\n| Pandit Indra\n|-\n| 6\n| \"Ek Surat Saloni Re Nainon Mein Bas Gayi\"\n|\n| Roopdas\n|-\n| 7\n| \"Bikhar Gayi Aasha Ki Badri Bikhar Gayi\"\n|Amirbai Karnataki\n| Roopdas\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id =0156994|title =Samaj Ko Badal Dalo (1947) }}\n\n{{Vijay Bhatt}}\n\n[[Category:1947 films]]\n[[Category:1940s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1940s drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vijay Bhatt]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Khemchand Prakash]]\n[[Category:Melodramas]]\n[[Category:Indian black-and-white films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Samaj Ko Badal Dalo\n| image          = Samaj_Ko_Badal_Dalo_(1947).jpg\n| image_size     = \n| caption        = \n| director       = [[Vijay Bhatt]]\n| producer       = Vijay Bhatt\n| writer         = Pandit Girish \n| story          = Pandit Girish\n| based on       = \n| narrator       = \n| starring       = [[Arun Kumar Ahuja|Arun Ahuja]]<br />Mridula<br />[[Yakub (actor)|Yakub]]<br />Leela Pawar\n| music          = [[Khemchand Prakash]]\n| cinematography = Yusuf Mulji\n| editing        = Pratap Dave\n| distributor    = \n| released       = 1947\n| runtime        = 133 min\n| country        = [[India]]\n| language       = [[Hindi language|Hindi]]\n| budget         = \n| gross          = \n| preceded_by    = \n| followed_by    = \n| website        = \n}}\n'''''Samaj Ko Badal Dalo''''' (Change This World) is a [[List of Bollywood films of 1947|1947]] [[Cinema of India|Indian]] [[Hindi]] social melodrama film directed by [[Vijay Bhatt]]. Produced under the Prakash Pictures banner,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gomolo.com/samaj-ko-badal-dalo-movie-cast-crew/1643|title=Samaj Ko Badal Dalo (1947)|publisher=Gomolo.com|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref> its music composer was [[Khemchand Prakash]], with lyrics by Pandit Indra, Roopdas, and [[Qamar Jalalabadi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myswar.com/album/samaaj-ko-badal-dalo-1947 |title=Album-Samaj Ko Badal Dalo (1947)|publisher=MySwar|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref> The story, screenplay and dialogues were by Pandit Girish. Its cinematographer was Yusuf Mulji and the film starred [[Arun Kumar Ahuja|Arun Ahuja]], Mridula, [[Yakub (actor)|Yakub]], Leela Pawar, Umakant and Bikram Kapoor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.citwf.com/film303846.htm|title=Samaj Ko Badal Dalo |publisher=Alan Goble|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nBhatt's social film dealt with the issue of \"mismatched\" marriages and advocated divorce, setting a partner free in order to choose their own mate.<ref name=\"Congress2007\">{{cite book|author=Indian History Congress|title=Proceedings - Indian History Congress|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GhVDAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=18 January 2015|year=2007}}</ref> ''[[Samaj Ko Badal Dalo]]'' (1970) is a film of the same name directed by [[V. Madhusudan Rao]] and produced by [[Gemini Studios|Gemini]], however it had no relation to the 1947 film,<ref name=\"RajadhyakshaWillemen2014\">{{cite book|author1=Ashish Rajadhyaksha|author2=Paul Willemen|author3=Professor of Critical Studies Paul Willemen|title=Encyclopedia of Indian Cinema|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SLkABAAAQBAJ&pg=PT67|accessdate=18 January 2015|date=10 July 2014|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-94318-9|pages=67\u2013}}</ref> but was instead a remake of [[A. Vincent]]'s award-winning [[Malayalam]] film, ''[[Thulabharam]]'' (1968)<ref name=\"Shankar\">{{cite book|title=Shankar's weekly|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FLQcAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=18 January 2015|year=1970}}</ref>\n\n==Plot==\nKishore ([[Arun Kumar Ahuja|Arun]]) and Manorama (Mridula) are in love, but unable to get married. Mridula's father is a clerk, who can't afford to pay the dowry demanded by Arun's family. Jayant ([[Yakub (actor)|Yakub]]) is a widower, and Mridula is married off to him. His cruel behaviour becomes apparent when he starts torturing Mridula soon after their marriage. Arun's parents get him married to the rich Champa (Leela Pawar), who is in love with someone else. Arun helps her get married to Naresh, the man she loves, by giving her a divorce. Arun watches the torture inflicted on Mridula and the story then continues through tense scenes where eventually Arun kills Jayant and unwittingly Mridula too, following which he's sent to a mental asylum having been declared insane.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Arun Kumar Ahuja|Arun]] as Kishore\n* Mridula Rani as Manorama\n* [[Yakub (actor)|Yakub]] as Jayant\n* Leela Pawar as Champa \n* Umakant\n* Bikram Kapoor\n* Prem Dhawan\n* Ramesh Sinha\n* Shabnam\n* Mohammed Rafi\n\n==Crew==\nThe film's crew consisted of:\n* Directed: [[Vijay Bhatt]]\n* Produced: Vijay Bhatt \n* Story: Pandit Girish\n* Screenplay: Pandit Girish\n* Dialogue: Pandit Girish\n* Cinematography: Yusuf Mulji\n* Choreography:\tSachin Shankar, Sharad Shukla\n* Editing: Pratap Dave\n* Art Direction: M. V. Dubashe, B. M. Shukla\n* Audiography: T. K. Dave\n* Music: [[Khemchand Prakash]]\n* Lyrics: Pandit Indra, Roopdas, [[Qamar Jalalabadi]]\n\n==Soundtrack==\n''Samaj Ko Badal Dalo'' was one of the early films for which [[Mohammed Rafi]] recorded songs in [[Bombay]]. The others were ''[[Gaon Ki Gori]]'' (1946) and ''[[Jugnu (1947 film)|Jugnu]]'' (1947).<ref name=\"Brittanica, India\">{{cite book|title=Students' Britannica India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ISFBJarYX7YC&pg=PA238|accessdate=18 January 2015|year=2000|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=978-0-85229-760-5|pages=238\u2013}}</ref> The music direction was by [[Khemchand Prakash]], with lyrics by Pandit Indra, Roopdas and [[Qamar Jalabadi]]. The playback singers were [[Mohammed Rafi]], [[Manna Dey]], [[Arun Kumar Ahuja]] and [[Amirbai Karnataki]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://muvyz.com/moviepage/ao993709/songs/#tabs|title=Songs Samaj Ko Badal Dalo (1947)|publisher=Muvyz, Inc|accessdate=18 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Song List===\n{| border=\"4\" cellpadding=\"7\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"margin: 1em 1em 1em 0; background: #f9f9f9; border: 1px #aaa solid; border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 95%;\"\n|- align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#cccccc\"\n! # !! Title !!Singer !! Lyricist \n|- \n| 1\n| \"Aye Ji Mat Pucho Kuch Baat\"\n| Mohammed Rafi, Manna Dey, Arun Kumar\n| Pandit Indra\n|-\n| 2\n| \"Dhire Dhire Chale Aao\"\n| \n|Pandit Indra\n|-\n| 3\n| \"Tu Kyun Yaad Aata Hai Yaad Aane Wale\"\n| \n| Qamar Jalalabadi\n|-\n| 4\n| \"Naina Ro Ro Ke Rah Gaye\"\n| [[Amirbai Karnataki]]\n| Roopdas\n|-\n| 5\n| \"Tori Unchi Atariya Pe Aaun Kaise\"\n|Zohrabai Ambalewali\n| Pandit Indra\n|-\n| 6\n| \"Ek Surat Saloni Re Nainon Mein Bas Gayi\"\n|\n| Roopdas\n|-\n| 7\n| \"Bikhar Gayi Aasha Ki Badri Bikhar Gayi\"\n|Amirbai Karnataki\n| Roopdas\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id =0156994|title =Samaj Ko Badal Dalo (1947) }}\n\n{{Vijay Bhatt}}\n\n[[Category:1947 films]]\n[[Category:1940s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:1940s drama films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Vijay Bhatt]]\n[[Category:Indian drama films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Khemchand Prakash]]\n[[Category:Melodramas]]\n[[Category:Indian black-and-white films]]\n", "name_user": "Jellysandwich0", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samaj_Ko_Badal_Dalo_(1947_film)"}
{"title_page": "Basheer Al Qudaimi", "text_new": "{{short description|Yemeni chess player}}\n{{Infobox chess player\n| name = Basheer Al Qudaimi\n| image = \n| birthname = \n| caption = \n| country = [[Yemen]]\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1984\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = \n| children =\n| title = [[FIDE titles|International Master (IM)]] (2008)\n| worldchampion = \n| womensworldchampion = \n| peakrating =\n| FideID = 9400346\n}}\n\n'''Basheer Al Qudaimi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0634\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u064a\u0645\u064a}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubaichess.ae/ar/2015/05/%d8%a3%d9%85%d9%8a%d9%86-%d9%88%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b3%d9%8a%d8%af-%d9%8a%d8%aa%d8%b4%d8%a7%d8%b1%d9%83%d8%a7%d9%86-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b5%d8%af%d8%a7%d8%b1%d8%a9-%d9%88%d8%a5%d8%b3%d8%ad%d8%a7%d9%82-%d9%8a/|title=\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u064a\u062a\u0634\u0627\u0631\u0643\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u062f\u0627\u0631\u0629 \u0648\u0625\u0633\u062d\u0627\u0642 \u064a\u0642\u0647\u0631 \u062d\u062f\u0648\u0634|first=|last=admin|date=30 May 2015|publisher=}}</ref> born 1984) is a [[Yemen]]i [[chess]] player who holds the title of [[FIDE titles|International Master (IM)]] (since 2008), and [[Arab Chess Championship]] winner (in 2007). He is the [[Chess Olympiad]] individual gold medal winner (in [[37th Chess Olympiad|2006]]).\n\n==Biography==\nIn 2003, Al Qudaimi with Yemen club ''Al-Wahda Sana'a'' won 3rd place in the Arab Club Chess Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olimpbase.org/2003ar/2003whda.html|title=OlimpBase :: 5th Arab Club Chess Championship, Damascus 2003, Al-Wahda Sana'a|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref> In 2007 in [[Taiz]], he won the [[Arab Chess Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chess-results.com/tnr9491.aspx?lan=1&art=4&turdet=YES&wi=821|title=Chess-Results Server Chess-results.com - Arab Men Chess Championship 2007|website=chess-results.com}}</ref>\n\nAl Qudaimi played for the Yemen team in the [[Chess Olympiad]]s:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olimpbase.org/players/pb3tz1xi.html|title=OlimpBase :: Men's Chess Olympiads :: Bashir Al-Qudaimi|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref>\n* In 2002, at second reserve board in the [[35th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Bled]] (+9, =1, -1),\n* In 2006, at reserve board in the [[37th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Turin]] (+7, =0, -0) and won individual gold medal,\n* In 2008, at reserve board in the [[38th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Dresden]] (+5, =2, -3),\n* In 2010, at second board in the [[39th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Khanty-Mansiysk]] (+3, =1, -6),\n* In 2014, at first board in the [[41st Chess Olympiad]] in [[Troms\u00f8]] (+4, =4, -2),\n* In 2018, at first board in the [[43rd Chess Olympiad]] in [[Batumi]] (+6, =2, -1)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chess-results.com/tnr368908.aspx?lan=1&art=20&fed=YEM&flag=30|title=Chess-Results Server Chess-results.com - 43rd Olympiad Batumi 2018 Open|website=chess-results.com}}</ref>.\n\nAlso he played for Yemen team in the [[Asian Games]] chess tournament (2010) and [[Pan Arab Games]] chess tournament (2007-2011), where he won individual gold medal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olimpbase.org/playersam/pb3tz1xi.html|title=OlimpBase :: Pan Arab Games (men) :: Bashir Al-Qudaimi|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Basheer Al Qudaimi awarded the FIDE International Master (IM) title.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{chessgames player|id=99216}}\n*[https://www.365chess.com/players/Basheer_Al_Qudaimi Basheer Al Qudaimi] chess games at 365chess.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qudaimi, Basheer Al}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Yemeni chess players]]\n[[Category:Chess Olympiad competitors]]\n[[Category:Chess International Masters]]\n\n{{Yemen-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Yemeni chess player}}\n{{Infobox chess player\n| name = Basheer Al Qudaimi\n| image = \n| birthname = \n| caption = \n| country = [[Yemen]]\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = 1984\n| birth_place = \n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| spouse = \n| children =\n| title = [[FIDE titles|International Master (IM)]] (2008)\n| worldchampion = \n| womensworldchampion = \n| peakrating =\n| FideID = 9400346\n}}\n\n'''Basheer Al Qudaimi''' ({{lang-ar|\u0628\u0634\u064a\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u062f\u064a\u0645\u064a}};<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dubaichess.ae/ar/2015/05/%d8%a3%d9%85%d9%8a%d9%86-%d9%88%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b3%d9%8a%d8%af-%d9%8a%d8%aa%d8%b4%d8%a7%d8%b1%d9%83%d8%a7%d9%86-%d8%a7%d9%84%d8%b5%d8%af%d8%a7%d8%b1%d8%a9-%d9%88%d8%a5%d8%b3%d8%ad%d8%a7%d9%82-%d9%8a/|title=\u0623\u0645\u064a\u0646 \u0648\u0627\u0644\u0633\u064a\u062f \u064a\u062a\u0634\u0627\u0631\u0643\u0627\u0646 \u0627\u0644\u0635\u062f\u0627\u0631\u0629 \u0648\u0625\u0633\u062d\u0627\u0642 \u064a\u0642\u0647\u0631 \u062d\u062f\u0648\u0634|first=|last=admin|date=30 May 2015|publisher=}}</ref> born 1984) is an [[Yemen]]i [[chess]] player who holds the title of [[FIDE titles|International Master (IM)]] (2008), [[Arab Chess Championship]] winner (2007). He is the [[Chess Olympiad]] individual gold medal winner ([[37th Chess Olympiad|2006]]).\n\n==Biography==\nIn 2003, Basheer Al Qudaimi with Yemen club ''Al-Wahda Sana'a'' won 3rd place in the Arab Club Chess Championship.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olimpbase.org/2003ar/2003whda.html|title=OlimpBase :: 5th Arab Club Chess Championship, Damascus 2003, Al-Wahda Sana'a|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref> In 2007, in [[Taiz]] he won [[Arab Chess Championship]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chess-results.com/tnr9491.aspx?lan=1&art=4&turdet=YES&wi=821|title=Chess-Results Server Chess-results.com - Arab Men Chess Championship 2007|website=chess-results.com}}</ref>\n\nBasheer Al Qudaimi played for Yemen team in the [[Chess Olympiad]]s:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olimpbase.org/players/pb3tz1xi.html|title=OlimpBase :: Men's Chess Olympiads :: Bashir Al-Qudaimi|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref>\n* In 2002, at second reserve board in the [[35th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Bled]] (+9, =1, -1),\n* In 2006, at reserve board in the [[37th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Turin]] (+7, =0, -0) and won individual gold medal,\n* In 2008, at reserve board in the [[38th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Dresden]] (+5, =2, -3),\n* In 2010, at second board in the [[39th Chess Olympiad]] in [[Khanty-Mansiysk]] (+3, =1, -6),\n* In 2014, at first board in the [[41st Chess Olympiad]] in [[Troms\u00f8]] (+4, =4, -2),\n* In 2018, at first board in the [[43rd Chess Olympiad]] in [[Batumi]] (+6, =2, -1)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chess-results.com/tnr368908.aspx?lan=1&art=20&fed=YEM&flag=30|title=Chess-Results Server Chess-results.com - 43rd Olympiad Batumi 2018 Open|website=chess-results.com}}</ref>.\n\nAlso he played for Yemen team in the [[Asian Games]] chess tournament (2010) and [[Pan Arab Games]] chess tournament (2007-2011), where won individual gold medal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.olimpbase.org/playersam/pb3tz1xi.html|title=OlimpBase :: Pan Arab Games (men) :: Bashir Al-Qudaimi|website=www.olimpbase.org}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Basheer Al Qudaimi awarded the FIDE International Master (IM) title.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{chessgames player|id=99216}}\n*[https://www.365chess.com/players/Basheer_Al_Qudaimi Basheer Al Qudaimi] chess games at 365chess.com\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Qudaimi, Basheer Al}}\n[[Category:1984 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Yemeni chess players]]\n[[Category:Chess Olympiad competitors]]\n[[Category:Chess International Masters]]\n\n{{Yemen-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "H elokeinu h 1", "label": "safe", "comment": "grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basheer_Al_Qudaimi"}
{"title_page": "B. R. Shetty", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty\n| image              = File:Dr BR Shetty Official Pic.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1942|08|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Udupi]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]] (now [[Karnataka]], India)\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = \n| known_for          = Founder and chairman, [[NMC Health]]\n| website            = {{url|brshetty.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty''' (born 1 August 1942) is an Indian-born [[billionaire]] businessman, and the founder of a number of companies based in the United Arab Emirates. He is founder and chairman of [[Abu Dhabi]]-based [[NMC Health]],<ref name=national/> and chairman of [[UAE Exchange]].<ref name=\"Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com\"/> He is also the founder and chairman of Neopharma, [[Finablr]] and BRS Ventures.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://businessworld.in/article/-I-Want-To-Be-The-No-1-Healthcare-Provider-In-India-Over-The-Next-10-Years-/23-03-2018-144373/| title=I Want To Be The No. 1 Healthcare Provider in India Over The Next 10 Years| author=Paramita Chatterjee, Suman K Jha| date=23 March 2018| publisher=BusinessWorld| access-date=8 May 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509012947/http://businessworld.in/article/-I-Want-To-Be-The-No-1-Healthcare-Provider-In-India-Over-The-Next-10-Years-/23-03-2018-144373/| archive-date=9 May 2018|url-status = live}}</ref> In 2018, the UAE Exchange brand became part of the financial services holding company, Finablr.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/en/billionaire-b-r-shetty-launches-new-financial-firms-holding-company-finablr/| title=Billionaire B.R. Shetty Launches New Financial Firms Holding Company Finablr| author=Mary Sophia| date=24 April 2018| publisher=Forbes Middle East| access-date=24 August 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825073919/https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/en/billionaire-b-r-shetty-launches-new-financial-firms-holding-company-finablr/| archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty's initial interest in 1975 was in hospitals and hospitality, and has since diversified into pharmaceuticals, financial services, retail, advertising and information technology.<ref name=\"Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-rich-list-in-full-342165.html#.V3JIbLh9600 | title=Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com | publisher=ArabianBusiness | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424235811/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-rich-list-in-full-342165.html#.V3JIbLh9600 | archive-date=24 April 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref> He was included on the ''[[Forbes]]'' list of India's 100 Richest People in 2015 and was listed as the 42nd richest person in 2020.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/| title=#47 B.R. Shetty| work=Forbes| accessdate=14 April 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228013207/http://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/| archive-date=28 December 2016|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/#6862cc8b6cc7| title=#42 B.R. Shetty| work=Forbes| accessdate=20 February 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514112322/https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/#6862cc8b6cc7| archive-date=14 May 2019| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere are allegations of misappropriation by Shetty at his companies and was forced to resign from his director positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/how-indian-billionaire-bavaguthu-raghuram-shetty-who-owned-2-floors-of-burj-khalifa-went-bust-2182896 | title=How Indian billionaire Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty went bust}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/healthcare/440371-billionaire-br-shetty-resigns-from-abu-dhabis-nmc-health | title=Billionaire BR Shetty resigns from Abu Dhabi's NMC Health}}</ref> On April 8, 2020, NMC went into Administration in UK due to the insolvency of the company due to alleged frauds committed by Shetty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nmc-insolvency-proceedings-inevitable-hospital-143125949.html | title=NMC into Administration}}</ref>\nDue to sharp drop in the share prices and Shetty pledging the shares for debts that he had incurred, it is believed that his net worth has fallen to fraction of the earlier estimate of $3.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfbusiness.com/uae-based-br-shettys-fortune-drops-1-5bn-since-muddy-waters-attack/ | title=\"BR Shetty's fortune drops by $1.5 Billion| date=26 January 2020}}</ref> Consequently, Forbes has dropped Shetty from its 2020 annual list of billionaires.\n\nShetty fled the UAE fearing legal procedure there by lender banks, including Dubai Islamic Bank and ADCB.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/banking-finance/444829-nmc-health-goes-into-administration-after-succumbing-to-creditors|title=NMC Health goes into administration after succumbing to creditors|website=ArabianBusiness.com}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nShetty was born in [[Kapu, Karnataka|Kapu]], [[Udupi]] to [[Tulu language|Tulu]] speaking parents Shambhu Shetty and Koosamma Shetty in the 1940s to an ethnic [[Tuluva]] family.<ref name = \"Mangalorean Tuluva\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mangaloretoday.com/gulfnews/Mangalorean-Tuluva-B-R-Shetty-buys-Travelex-for-1-billion.html |title=Mangalorean Tuluva B R Shetty Buy's Travelex for 1 billion |date=14 June 2015 |accessdate=12 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802204342/http://www.mangaloretoday.com/gulfnews/Mangalorean-Tuluva-B-R-Shetty-buys-Travelex-for-1-billion.html |archive-date=2 August 2017 |url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty completed his pharmaceutical education in [[India]] and also served as the Vice-Chairman of the Municipal Council in Udupi. He married Chandrakumari Shetty and has four children.<ref name=\"Journey - Dr. B. R. Shetty\">{{cite web | url=http://www.brshetty.com/journey/ | title=Journey \u2013 Dr. B. R. Shetty | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614205457/http://www.brshetty.com/journey/ | archive-date=14 June 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShetty immigrated to the UAE in 1973. After working as the country's first medical representative,<ref name=national/> he founded [[NMC Health|New Medical Centre Health]] (NMC) in 1975 to fill the need for personalized, cost-effective healthcare accessible to all.<ref name=national/><ref name=namma>{{cite web| url=http://namma.tv/dr-b-r-shetty-to-build-abu-dhabis-first-medical-university-in-honour-of-sheikh-zayed/| title=Dr B.R.Shetty to build Abu Dhabi's first medical university in honour of Sheikh Zayed| date=24 June 2016| publisher=NamMa TV| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802174516/http://namma.tv/dr-b-r-shetty-to-build-abu-dhabis-first-medical-university-in-honour-of-sheikh-zayed/| archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> At that time, his wife was the only doctor in the clinic.<ref name=emi/> NMC is now the largest private healthcare provider in the UAE with over four million patients annually across 45 facilities spread over 12 cities and 8 countries, including UAE, KSA, Oman, Spain, Italy, Denmark, Colombia and Brazil. It is the first healthcare company from the GCC and the first company from Abu Dhabi to be listed on the premium segment of the [[London Stock Exchange]] and is part of the coveted [[FTSE 100 Index]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/09/02/gulf-private-hospitals-group-nmc-eyes-uk-launch-leap-ftse-100/|title=Gulf private hospitals group NMC eyes UK launch after leap into FTSE 100|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=2 September 2017|access-date=24 September 2017|first=Iain|last=Withers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913030605/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/09/02/gulf-private-hospitals-group-nmc-eyes-uk-launch-leap-ftse-100/|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty established the [[UAE Exchange]] in 1980 in an attempt to ease the process of sending money by the expats to their families in their respective home countries. By 2016, it had expanded into over 31 countries and had approximately 800 direct offices. In 2014, it did over US$50 billion collectively in money remittance and exchange volumes.<ref name=emi>{{cite web| url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/dubai-dreams-from-jobless-medical-rep-to-billions-br-shetty-2016-08-10-1.638590| title=Dubai Dreams: From jobless medical rep to billions - BR Shetty| author=VM Sathish| date=10 August 2016| publisher=Emirates 24/7| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606205018/http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/dubai-dreams-from-jobless-medical-rep-to-billions-br-shetty-2016-08-10-1.638590| archive-date=6 June 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty acquired [[Travelex]], a major foreign exchange company, in 2014.<ref name=national>{{cite web| url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/economics/br-shetty-the-astute-businessman-who-turned-8-into-1bn#full| title=BR Shetty, the astute businessman who turned $8 into $1bn| author=Frank Kane| date=1 July 2014| publisher=The National| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428185222/http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/economics/br-shetty-the-astute-businessman-who-turned-8-into-1bn#full| archive-date=28 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=khal/> Travelex has a global footprint including 1500 stores and 1300 ATMs across 27 countries.\n\nIn 2003, Shetty founded NMC Neopharma, a UAE based pharmaceutical manufacturer.<ref name=emi/> Inaugurated by the then President of India, [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]] in Abu Dhabi, Neopharma is centered on using the concept of modular manufacturing following global benchmarks in manufacturing technology and putting in place efficient control mechanisms. Neopharma has a research and development wing and works to provide quality medicines at affordable prices. The company also contracts manufacturing for international pharmaceutical companies as well as generic brands for companies including, but not limited to, [[Merck Group|Merck]], [[Pfizer]], [[AstraZeneca]], and [[Boots UK]].<ref name=emi/>\n\nIn 2012, Shetty led NMC through an [[initial public offering|IPO]] on the [[London Stock Exchange]], which raised $330 million. The funds went towards building a specialty hospital in [[Khalifa City]], Abu Dhabi.<ref name=gulfnews>{{cite web| url=http://gulfnews.com/business/sectors/general/dr-b-r-shetty-to-expand-his-nmc-group-in-uae-and-gcc-1.1400467| title=Dr B.R. Shetty to expand his NMC group in UAE and GCC| author=Fareed Rahman| date=18 October 2014| publisher=Gulf News| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006162305/http://gulfnews.com/business/sectors/general/dr-b-r-shetty-to-expand-his-nmc-group-in-uae-and-gcc-1.1400467| archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Shetty announced that he was building the first medical university in Abu Dhabi in honor of [[Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan|Sheikh Zayed]].<ref name=namma/> That same month, he was elected to be chairman of the Indian Business/Professional Group.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bfirst.in/news/diaspora/8815/br-shetty-wants-promote-india-uae-ties-through-ibpg| title=BR Shetty wants to promote India-UAE ties through IBPG| date=7 June 2016| publisher=Bfirst| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925083522/http://www.bfirst.in/news/diaspora/8815/br-shetty-wants-promote-india-uae-ties-through-ibpg| archive-date=25 September 2017| url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2016, Shetty announced that he was building a 400-bed super-specialty hospital in Udupi in Karnataka through B R S Ventures.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mangalorean.com/dr-br-shetty-build-400-bed-super-speciality-hospital-udupi/| title=Dr BR Shetty to Build 400-bed Super-specialty hospital in Udupi| date=25 August 2016| publisher=Mangalorean| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925132051/https://www.mangalorean.com/dr-br-shetty-build-400-bed-super-speciality-hospital-udupi/| archive-date=25 September 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty also owned a hospital in [[Alexandria]], two hospitals in Nepal, and acquired a hospital in Cairo as part of his personal portfolio under the same company.<ref name=gulfnews/>\n\nIn August 2019, BRS Ventures announced plans to invest $5 billion in developing healthcare facilities across India.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/jang-sangh-hand-billionaire-b-r-shetty-5-billion-dollar-investments-in-indian-healthcare/story/373353.html | title=Old Jan Sangh hand, billionaire B R Shetty plans $5 billion investment in Indian healthcare | publisher=Business Today | accessdate=25 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825084836/https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/jang-sangh-hand-billionaire-b-r-shetty-5-billion-dollar-investments-in-indian-healthcare/story/373353.html | archive-date=25 August 2019 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[Bloomberg News]] report casted doubts on his real holding amidst the short-selling of NMC Health by [[Muddy Waters Research]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/business/a-jet-setting-billionaire-had-it-all-then-carson-block-came-along/articleshow/74204580.cms|title=Jet-setting billionaire Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty had it all. Then Carson Block came along| publisher=Bloomberg| accessdate= 20 February 2020}}</ref> Also in February 2020, Shetty was ousted from the NMC Health board following a corporate governance scandal over his holdings in the company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correspondent|first=Ben Martin, Senior City|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nmcs-founder-forced-out-over-shares-scandal-cr59jz2s6|title=NMC's founder forced out over shares scandal|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, 2020, NMC went into Administration in UK due to the insolvency of the company due to alleged frauds committed by Shetty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nmc-insolvency-proceedings-inevitable-hospital-143125949.html|title=NMC Heads to Administration After Giving In to Creditor Demands|website=finance.yahoo.com}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nShetty has invested in a medical institution in the north Indian state of Uttarakhand. He is the founder and patron of the Indian Pharmaceutical Association in the Emirates, and is a member of the Advisory Board (Financial Sector), Economic Department, Government of Dubai, UAE and the Pharmaceutical Committee, Dubai. He is also the chairman of [[Abu Dhabi Indian School]] and Bright Riders School.<ref name=\"Indian tycoons storm Arabian Business Expat Power List 2011 - ArabianBusiness.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-tycoons-storm-arabian-business-expat-power-list-2011-383132.html#.V3JKfbh9600 | title=Indian tycoons storm Arabian Business Expat Power List 2011 - ArabianBusiness.com | publisher=ArabianBusiness | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815070908/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-tycoons-storm-arabian-business-expat-power-list-2011-383132.html#.V3JKfbh9600 | archive-date=15 August 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brightriders.ae/?page_id=176|title=Chairman's Message {{!}} Bright Riders School, Abu Dhabi|website=brightriders.ae|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802164450/http://brightriders.ae/?page_id=176|archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Shetty was elected as the Chairman to the board of directors of UAE Exchange.<ref name=khal>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/dr-br-shetty-takes-over-as-chairman-of-uae-exchange|title=Dr B.R. Shetty takes over as chairman of UAE Exchange|work=Khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085905/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/dr-br-shetty-takes-over-as-chairman-of-uae-exchange|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uae-exchange-appoints-b-r-shetty-as-chairman-promoth-manghat-as-ceo/articleshow/48652739.cms|title=UAE Exchange appoints B R Shetty as Chairman, Promoth Manghat as CEO|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=24 August 2015|publisher=Economic Times India|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424090633/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uae-exchange-appoints-b-r-shetty-as-chairman-promoth-manghat-as-ceo/articleshow/48652739.cms|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> He was named chairman of The Indian Business/Professional Group in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/dr-b-r-shetty-to-head-the-indian-businessprofessional-group|title=Dr B R Shetty to head The Indian Business/Professional Group|publisher=News Karnataka|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085646/http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/dr-b-r-shetty-to-head-the-indian-businessprofessional-group|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> H. H. Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid al Maktoum nominated Shetty as a member of the UAE medical council in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bfirst.in/news/2016_09_09/12860|title=Businessman BR Shetty nominated to medical council by PM of Dubai|publisher=Bfirst}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Shetty announced that he would invest Rs 1000 crore ($157.3 million) to produce a film with director [[V. A. Shrikumar Menon]]. The film, starring [[Mohanlal]], was to be based on the novel [[Randamoozham]], a retelling of [[Mahabharata]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Billionaire B. R. Shetty aims for $1 billion in revenue from Indian film epic|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/nmc-health-shetty-film/billionaire-b-r-shetty-aims-for-1-billion-in-revenue-from-indian-film-epic-idINKBN18V0SR|access-date=28 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027181423/https://in.reuters.com/article/nmc-health-shetty-film/billionaire-b-r-shetty-aims-for-1-billion-in-revenue-from-indian-film-epic-idINKBN18V0SR|archive-date=27 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\nIn May 2019, however, the film was shelved due to creative issues.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mohanlal's Rs 1000 crore film project 'Randamoozham' shelved|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2019/apr/03/mohanlals-rs-1000-crore-film-project-randamoozham-shelved-1959795.html|access-date=20 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805223955/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2019/apr/03/mohanlals-rs-1000-crore-film-project-randamoozham-shelved-1959795.html|archive-date=5 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n{{Overly detailed|Section|date=February 2020}}\nIn 2005, Shetty was awarded the highest civilian distinction in the Emirate, the [[Abu Dhabi Awards]].<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty-1.119120 | title = Abu Dhabi Awards: B R Shetty | date = 23 May 2015 | work = The National | access-date = 23 September 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190923071607/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty-1.119120 | archive-date = 23 September 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> Given by H. H. Sheikh [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan]], the Crown Prince of Abu Dhabi, the first year the distinction was awarded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty|title=Abu Dhabi Awards: B R Shetty|publisher=The National|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422235344/http://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty|archive-date=22 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Also in 2005, U.S. India Friendship Society presented Shetty the Distinguished Entrepreneur Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neopharmauae.com/en/news.asp?News_Id=173-Dr.-B.R.-Shetty-received-The-Distinguished-Entrepreneur-Award-from-the-US-India-Friendship-Society-|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty received The Distinguished Entrepreneur Award from the US India Friendship Society|publisher=Neopharma|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173745/http://www.neopharmauae.com/en/news.asp?News_Id=173-Dr.-B.R.-Shetty-received-The-Distinguished-Entrepreneur-Award-from-the-US-India-Friendship-Society-|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nShetty was honoured by the [[Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]] in 2007.<ref name=\"The recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman - Times of India\">{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/The-recipients-of-Pravasi-Bharatiya-Samman/articleshow/1113368.cms | title=The recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman \u2013 Times of India | work=Times of India| accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"New Delhi B R Shetty Among Padma Shree Awardees\">{{cite web | url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=56080 | title=New Delhi B R Shetty Among Padma Shree Awardees | publisher=Daijiworld Media Pvt Ltd Mangalore | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170744/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=56080 | archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nErnst & Young Middle East honored Shetty with the Entrepreneur of the year finalist award in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/eb247/companies-markets/five-uae-execs-in-running-for-ernst-young-award-2008-01-17-1.216304|title=Five UAE execs in running for Ernst & Young award|publisher=Emirates 24/7|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085817/http://www.emirates247.com/eb247/companies-markets/five-uae-execs-in-running-for-ernst-young-award-2008-01-17-1.216304|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty received the [[Padma Shri|Padmashree]] awarded by the [[President of India]] in 2009 for his contribution in the field of trade and industry.<ref name=\"IBPC Felicitates Padma Shri Award Winners - Khaleej Times\">{{cite web | url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/ibpc-felicitates-padma-shri-award-winners | title=IBPC Felicitates Padma Shri Award Winners \u2013 Khaleej Times | work=Khaleej Times| accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808123305/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/ibpc-felicitates-padma-shri-award-winners | archive-date=8 August 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, he received the Asian Achievers Award from the Human Achievers Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/article/20110713/ARTICLE/307139999/1002|title=Asian Achievers Awards for Dhahi Khalfan, others|work=Khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174100/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/article/20110713/ARTICLE/307139999/1002|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Pharma Leaders founded by Satya Brahma declared Shetty as Global Indian of the Year along with [[Kiran Mazumdar-Shaw|Kiran Mazumdar Shaw]] at 5th Annual Pharmaceutical Leadership Summit & Pharma Leaders Business Leadership Awards 2012 in Mumbai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pharmaleaders.tv/biocon-chief-dr-kiran-majumdar-shaw-nmc-chief-dr-b-r-shetty-declared-global-indian-of-the-year-2/|title=Biocon Chief Dr. Kiran Majumdar Shaw & NMC Chief Dr B.R.Shetty Declared Global Indian of the Year {{!}} Pharmaleaders TV|website=pharmaleaders.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024205347/http://pharmaleaders.tv/biocon-chief-dr-kiran-majumdar-shaw-nmc-chief-dr-b-r-shetty-declared-global-indian-of-the-year-2/|archive-date=24 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Shetty was recognized as one of Asia's most promising leaders at the Asian Brand & Leadership Summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=189157|title=UAE Exchange named leader, most promising brand in Asia|publisher=Daiji World|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085721/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=189157|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In March 2013, he was awarded the International Achievers Summit's Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty receives Lifetime Achievement Award|publisher=NMC Trading|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174516/http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, Shetty received the Asian Business Leadership Forum India-UAE Business Icons Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ablfawards.com/2013-winners/|title=ABLF Awards 2013 Winners|publisher=ABLF|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211033716/http://www.ablfawards.com/2013-winners/|archive-date=11 December 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref> He also received the 2013 Frost & Sullivan Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frost.com/prod/servlet/press-release.pag?docid=291322634|title=Dr. B R Shetty honoured with Frost & Sullivan - Lifetime Achievement Award for the Year 2013|publisher=Frost & Sullivan|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425031103/https://www.frost.com/prod/servlet/press-release.pag?docid=291322634|archive-date=25 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Forbes Middle East recognized Shetty with the Top Indian Leaders in the UAE Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/forbes-middle-east-unveils-top-indian-leaders-in-the-arab-region|title=Forbes Middle East Reveals Top Indian Leaders in the Arab World|website=Forbes Middle East|publisher=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He also received the Lakshya Business Visionary Award in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/getahead/report/achievers-from-salesman-to-biz-tycoon-a-serial-entrepreneurs-success-mantras/20141105.htm|title=From salesman to biz tycoon: A serial entrepreneur's success mantras|publisher=Rediff|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173734/http://www.rediff.com/getahead/report/achievers-from-salesman-to-biz-tycoon-a-serial-entrepreneurs-success-mantras/20141105.htm|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, Shetty was recognized with the International Achievement Award at the Indian Innovator Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/entmagazineme/docs/entrepreneur_middle_east_january_20|title=Indian Innovator Awards 2014|publisher=Entrepreneur Middle East|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173725/https://issuu.com/entmagazineme/docs/entrepreneur_middle_east_january_20|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, the Indian Club - Bahrain recognized Shetty with a Centenary Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=295424|title=Bahrain : Dr Kalam presents Indian Club Centenary awards to Colaco, B R Shetty|publisher=Daiji World|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085429/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=295424|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> He received the Deal of the Year Award at the 2015 Indian CEO Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/sunil-vaswani-takes-top-honours-at-indian-ceo-awards-582410.html|title=Sunil Vaswani takes top honours at Indian CEO Awards|publisher=Arabian Business|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008135040/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/sunil-vaswani-takes-top-honours-at-indian-ceo-awards-582410.html|archive-date=8 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In June 2015, Shetty received the Business Personality of the Year award from Crowe Horwath International.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-has-received-the-prestigious-business-personality-of-the-year-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty has received the prestigious Business Personality of the Year award|publisher=NMV Health|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150805020024/http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-has-received-the-prestigious-business-personality-of-the-year-award/|archive-date=5 August 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> That same month, Shetty received the Arabian Indian Czars award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-06-18/news/63567767_1_fadnavis-sunil-vaswani-rizwan-sajan|title=Arabian Indian Czars Award: Times Now felicitates successful Indians in Middle East|work=The Economic Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018060431/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-06-18/news/63567767_1_fadnavis-sunil-vaswani-rizwan-sajan|archive-date=18 October 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty received the Global Indian Achiever Award in 2015 from H. H. Sheikh Nahyan Bin Mubarak al Nahyan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-global-indian-achiever-award/|title=Dr. B R Shetty honoured with Global Indian Achiever Award|publisher=NMC Health|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031042109/http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-global-indian-achiever-award/|archive-date=31 October 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Also in 2015, H. H. Prince Faisal Bin Saud Bin Musaed Bin Abdulaziz presented Shetty with the National Cultural Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sauress.com/en/saudigazette/240107|title=Indian tycoon Shetty is honored with National Cultural Award|work=The Saudi Gazette|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173839/http://www.sauress.com/en/saudigazette/240107|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty's company, NMC Healthcare, received the Frost & Sullivan Middle East Integrated Healthcare Company of the Year Award in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfinance.com/infrastructure-investment/nmc-guides-the-way-for-the-uaes-healthcare-sector|title=NMC guides the way for the UAE's healthcare sector|publisher=World Finance|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170430214825/http://www.worldfinance.com/infrastructure-investment/nmc-guides-the-way-for-the-uaes-healthcare-sector|archive-date=30 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, MILAAP honored Shetty with a Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award-3/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty receives Lifetime Achievement Award|publisher=NMC Trading|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174031/http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award-3/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2015 Gulf Business Industry Awards, Shetty was recognized as the Healthcare Business Leader of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfbusiness.com/gulf-business-industry-awards-2015-business-leaders-year/|title=Gulf Business Industry Awards 2015: Business Leaders of the Year|date=9 September 2015|publisher=Gulf Business|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173736/http://gulfbusiness.com/gulf-business-industry-awards-2015-business-leaders-year/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In November 2015, he was felicitated by More Ignatius Jacobite Syrian Orthodox Cathedral in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brshetty.com/awards/dr-b-r-shetty-felicitated-by-mor-ignatius-jacobite-syrian-orthodox-cathedral/|title=Dr. B.R.Setty Felicitated By Mor Ignatius Jacobite Syrian Orthodox Cathedral, Dubai|publisher=Dr. B. R. Shetty|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424175818/http://www.brshetty.com/awards/dr-b-r-shetty-felicitated-by-mor-ignatius-jacobite-syrian-orthodox-cathedral/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Shetty's NMC Healthcare was recognized at the 6th Middle East Business Leaders Awards in 2015, where Shetty was given the Industry Excellence in Healthcare Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/mebla-honours-industry-leaders|title=Mebla honours industry leaders|work=khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085800/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/mebla-honours-industry-leaders|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Shetty received the Golden Peacock Lifetime Achievement Award for Business Leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenpeacockaward.com/past-winners/individual-leadership-awards.html|title=Roll of Honour|publisher=Golden Peacock Awards|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173821/http://www.goldenpeacockaward.com/past-winners/individual-leadership-awards.html|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Also in 2016, Shetty won the Business Excellence Award from the Indian Business & Professional Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/news/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-with-business-excellence-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty honoured with Business Excellence Award|publisher=NMC Health|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085934/http://www.nmchealth.com/news/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-with-business-excellence-award/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Middlesex University in Dubai awarded Shetty an Honorary Doctorate in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdx.ac.ae/about-us/honorary-doctorates|title=Middlesex Dubai Honorary Graduates|publisher=Middlesex University Dubai|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174731/http://www.mdx.ac.ae/about-us/honorary-doctorates|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Shetty was honored at the Annual Health Awards with a special award for his contribution to the region's healthcare industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://article.wn.com/view/2017/01/23/Dr_B_R_Shetty_honoured_at_the_Annual_Health_Awards_2017_NMC_/|title=Dr. B. R. Shetty honoured at the Annual Health Awards 2017 (NMC Health plc)|publisher=World News|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085508/https://article.wn.com/view/2017/01/23/Dr_B_R_Shetty_honoured_at_the_Annual_Health_Awards_2017_NMC_/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> The following month, Shetty received the Nadaprabhu Kempegowda International Award at the Kempegowda International Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/kempegowda-international-festival-lays-emphasis-on-uniting-okkaligas-under-roof|title=Kempegowda International Festival lays emphasis on uniting Okkaligas under roof|publisher=News Karnataka|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174146/http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/kempegowda-international-festival-lays-emphasis-on-uniting-okkaligas-under-roof|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Shetty was recognized by Forbes Middle East among the top Indian leaders in the Arab world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/revealed-top-indian-business-leaders-in-arab-world-1.2218991|title=Revealed: Top Indian business leaders in Arab world|publisher=Gulf News Business|accessdate=25 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527090500/https://gulfnews.com/business/revealed-top-indian-business-leaders-in-arab-world-1.2218991|archive-date=27 May 2019|url-status = live}}</ref> In September 2018 Shetty received the C3 Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/c3-us-arab-healthcare--business-summit-and-title-sponsor-alitheia-holdings-honors-keynote-speaker-dr-br-shetty-with-lifetime-achievement-award-300714982.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=25 August 2019|title=C3 US-Arab Healthcare & Business Summit and Title Sponsor Alitheia Holdings Honors Keynote Speaker Dr. B.R. Shetty with Lifetime Achievement Award|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825020538/https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/c3-us-arab-healthcare--business-summit-and-title-sponsor-alitheia-holdings-honors-keynote-speaker-dr-br-shetty-with-lifetime-achievement-award-300714982.html|archive-date=25 August 2019|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.brshetty.com/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shetty, B. R.}}\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Mangaloreans]]\n[[Category:Tulu people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in trade and industry]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Udupi district]]\n[[Category:Indian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian businesspeople]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty\n| image              = File:Dr BR Shetty Official Pic.jpg\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date and age|1942|08|01|df=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Udupi]], [[Madras Presidency]], [[British India]] (now [[Karnataka]], India)\n| death_date         = \n| death_place        = \n| occupation         = \n| known_for          = Founder and chairman, [[NMC Health]]\n| website            = {{url|brshetty.com/}}\n}}\n\n'''Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty''' (born 1 August 1942) is an Indian-born [[billionaire]] businessman, and the founder of a number of companies based in the United Arab Emirates. He is founder and chairman of [[Abu Dhabi]]-based [[NMC Health]],<ref name=national/> and chairman of [[UAE Exchange]].<ref name=\"Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com\"/> He is also the founder and chairman of Neopharma, [[Finablr]] and BRS Ventures.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://businessworld.in/article/-I-Want-To-Be-The-No-1-Healthcare-Provider-In-India-Over-The-Next-10-Years-/23-03-2018-144373/| title=I Want To Be The No. 1 Healthcare Provider in India Over The Next 10 Years| author=Paramita Chatterjee, Suman K Jha| date=23 March 2018| publisher=BusinessWorld| access-date=8 May 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180509012947/http://businessworld.in/article/-I-Want-To-Be-The-No-1-Healthcare-Provider-In-India-Over-The-Next-10-Years-/23-03-2018-144373/| archive-date=9 May 2018|url-status = live}}</ref> In 2018, the UAE Exchange brand became part of the financial services holding company, Finablr.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/en/billionaire-b-r-shetty-launches-new-financial-firms-holding-company-finablr/| title=Billionaire B.R. Shetty Launches New Financial Firms Holding Company Finablr| author=Mary Sophia| date=24 April 2018| publisher=Forbes Middle East| access-date=24 August 2018| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180825073919/https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/en/billionaire-b-r-shetty-launches-new-financial-firms-holding-company-finablr/| archive-date=25 August 2018|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty's initial interest in 1975 was in hospitals and hospitality, and has since diversified into pharmaceuticals, financial services, retail, advertising and information technology.<ref name=\"Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-rich-list-in-full-342165.html#.V3JIbLh9600 | title=Indian Rich List in full - ArabianBusiness.com | publisher=ArabianBusiness | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424235811/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-rich-list-in-full-342165.html#.V3JIbLh9600 | archive-date=24 April 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref> He was included on the ''[[Forbes]]'' list of India's 100 Richest People in 2015 and was listed as the 42nd richest person in 2020.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/| title=#47 B.R. Shetty| work=Forbes| accessdate=14 April 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161228013207/http://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/| archive-date=28 December 2016|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/#6862cc8b6cc7| title=#42 B.R. Shetty| work=Forbes| accessdate=20 February 2020| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514112322/https://www.forbes.com/profile/br-shetty/#6862cc8b6cc7| archive-date=14 May 2019| url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThere are allegations of misappropriation by Shetty at his companies and was forced to resign from his director positions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/how-indian-billionaire-bavaguthu-raghuram-shetty-who-owned-2-floors-of-burj-khalifa-went-bust-2182896 | title=How Indian billionaire Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty went bust}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/healthcare/440371-billionaire-br-shetty-resigns-from-abu-dhabis-nmc-health | title=Billionaire BR Shetty resigns from Abu Dhabi's NMC Health}}</ref> On April 8, 2020, NMC went into Administration in UK due to the insolvency of the company due to alleged frauds committed by Shetty.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nmc-insolvency-proceedings-inevitable-hospital-143125949.html | title=NMC into Administration}}</ref>\nDue to sharp drop in the share prices and Shetty pledging the shares for debts that he had incurred, it is believed that his net worth has fallen to fraction of the earlier estimate of $3.5 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfbusiness.com/uae-based-br-shettys-fortune-drops-1-5bn-since-muddy-waters-attack/ | title=\"BR Shetty's fortune drops by $1.5 Billion| date=26 January 2020}}</ref> Consequently, Forbes has dropped Shetty from its list of billionaires.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nShetty fled the UAE fearing legal procedure there by lender banks, including Dubai Islamic Bank and ADCB.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arabianbusiness.com/banking-finance/444829-nmc-health-goes-into-administration-after-succumbing-to-creditors|title=NMC Health goes into administration after succumbing to creditors|website=ArabianBusiness.com}}</ref> \n\n==Early life==\nShetty was born in [[Kapu, Karnataka|Kapu]], [[Udupi]] to [[Tulu language|Tulu]] speaking parents Shambhu Shetty and Koosamma Shetty in the 1940s to an ethnic [[Tuluva]] family.<ref name = \"Mangalorean Tuluva\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mangaloretoday.com/gulfnews/Mangalorean-Tuluva-B-R-Shetty-buys-Travelex-for-1-billion.html |title=Mangalorean Tuluva B R Shetty Buy's Travelex for 1 billion |date=14 June 2015 |accessdate=12 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802204342/http://www.mangaloretoday.com/gulfnews/Mangalorean-Tuluva-B-R-Shetty-buys-Travelex-for-1-billion.html |archive-date=2 August 2017 |url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty completed his pharmaceutical education in [[India]] and also served as the Vice-Chairman of the Municipal Council in Udupi. He married Chandrakumari Shetty and has four children.<ref name=\"Journey - Dr. B. R. Shetty\">{{cite web | url=http://www.brshetty.com/journey/ | title=Journey \u2013 Dr. B. R. Shetty | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160614205457/http://www.brshetty.com/journey/ | archive-date=14 June 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nShetty immigrated to the UAE in 1973. After working as the country's first medical representative,<ref name=national/> he founded [[NMC Health|New Medical Centre Health]] (NMC) in 1975 to fill the need for personalized, cost-effective healthcare accessible to all.<ref name=national/><ref name=namma>{{cite web| url=http://namma.tv/dr-b-r-shetty-to-build-abu-dhabis-first-medical-university-in-honour-of-sheikh-zayed/| title=Dr B.R.Shetty to build Abu Dhabi's first medical university in honour of Sheikh Zayed| date=24 June 2016| publisher=NamMa TV| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802174516/http://namma.tv/dr-b-r-shetty-to-build-abu-dhabis-first-medical-university-in-honour-of-sheikh-zayed/| archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> At that time, his wife was the only doctor in the clinic.<ref name=emi/> NMC is now the largest private healthcare provider in the UAE with over four million patients annually across 45 facilities spread over 12 cities and 8 countries, including UAE, KSA, Oman, Spain, Italy, Denmark, Colombia and Brazil. It is the first healthcare company from the GCC and the first company from Abu Dhabi to be listed on the premium segment of the [[London Stock Exchange]] and is part of the coveted [[FTSE 100 Index]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/09/02/gulf-private-hospitals-group-nmc-eyes-uk-launch-leap-ftse-100/|title=Gulf private hospitals group NMC eyes UK launch after leap into FTSE 100|newspaper=The Telegraph|date=2 September 2017|access-date=24 September 2017|first=Iain|last=Withers|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170913030605/http://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2017/09/02/gulf-private-hospitals-group-nmc-eyes-uk-launch-leap-ftse-100/|archive-date=13 September 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty established the [[UAE Exchange]] in 1980 in an attempt to ease the process of sending money by the expats to their families in their respective home countries. By 2016, it had expanded into over 31 countries and had approximately 800 direct offices. In 2014, it did over US$50 billion collectively in money remittance and exchange volumes.<ref name=emi>{{cite web| url=http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/dubai-dreams-from-jobless-medical-rep-to-billions-br-shetty-2016-08-10-1.638590| title=Dubai Dreams: From jobless medical rep to billions - BR Shetty| author=VM Sathish| date=10 August 2016| publisher=Emirates 24/7| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170606205018/http://www.emirates247.com/news/emirates/dubai-dreams-from-jobless-medical-rep-to-billions-br-shetty-2016-08-10-1.638590| archive-date=6 June 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty acquired [[Travelex]], a major foreign exchange company, in 2014.<ref name=national>{{cite web| url=http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/economics/br-shetty-the-astute-businessman-who-turned-8-into-1bn#full| title=BR Shetty, the astute businessman who turned $8 into $1bn| author=Frank Kane| date=1 July 2014| publisher=The National| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170428185222/http://www.thenational.ae/business/industry-insights/economics/br-shetty-the-astute-businessman-who-turned-8-into-1bn#full| archive-date=28 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref><ref name=khal/> Travelex has a global footprint including 1500 stores and 1300 ATMs across 27 countries.\n\nIn 2003, Shetty founded NMC Neopharma, a UAE based pharmaceutical manufacturer.<ref name=emi/> Inaugurated by the then President of India, [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]] in Abu Dhabi, Neopharma is centered on using the concept of modular manufacturing following global benchmarks in manufacturing technology and putting in place efficient control mechanisms. Neopharma has a research and development wing and works to provide quality medicines at affordable prices. The company also contracts manufacturing for international pharmaceutical companies as well as generic brands for companies including, but not limited to, [[Merck Group|Merck]], [[Pfizer]], [[AstraZeneca]], and [[Boots UK]].<ref name=emi/>\n\nIn 2012, Shetty led NMC through an [[initial public offering|IPO]] on the [[London Stock Exchange]], which raised $330 million. The funds went towards building a specialty hospital in [[Khalifa City]], Abu Dhabi.<ref name=gulfnews>{{cite web| url=http://gulfnews.com/business/sectors/general/dr-b-r-shetty-to-expand-his-nmc-group-in-uae-and-gcc-1.1400467| title=Dr B.R. Shetty to expand his NMC group in UAE and GCC| author=Fareed Rahman| date=18 October 2014| publisher=Gulf News| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161006162305/http://gulfnews.com/business/sectors/general/dr-b-r-shetty-to-expand-his-nmc-group-in-uae-and-gcc-1.1400467| archive-date=6 October 2016|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2016, Shetty announced that he was building the first medical university in Abu Dhabi in honor of [[Zayed bin Sultan Al Nahyan|Sheikh Zayed]].<ref name=namma/> That same month, he was elected to be chairman of the Indian Business/Professional Group.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.bfirst.in/news/diaspora/8815/br-shetty-wants-promote-india-uae-ties-through-ibpg| title=BR Shetty wants to promote India-UAE ties through IBPG| date=7 June 2016| publisher=Bfirst| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925083522/http://www.bfirst.in/news/diaspora/8815/br-shetty-wants-promote-india-uae-ties-through-ibpg| archive-date=25 September 2017| url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2016, Shetty announced that he was building a 400-bed super-specialty hospital in Udupi in Karnataka through B R S Ventures.<ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.mangalorean.com/dr-br-shetty-build-400-bed-super-speciality-hospital-udupi/| title=Dr BR Shetty to Build 400-bed Super-specialty hospital in Udupi| date=25 August 2016| publisher=Mangalorean| accessdate=2 May 2017| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170925132051/https://www.mangalorean.com/dr-br-shetty-build-400-bed-super-speciality-hospital-udupi/| archive-date=25 September 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty also owned a hospital in [[Alexandria]], two hospitals in Nepal, and acquired a hospital in Cairo as part of his personal portfolio under the same company.<ref name=gulfnews/>\n\nIn August 2019, BRS Ventures announced plans to invest $5 billion in developing healthcare facilities across India.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/jang-sangh-hand-billionaire-b-r-shetty-5-billion-dollar-investments-in-indian-healthcare/story/373353.html | title=Old Jan Sangh hand, billionaire B R Shetty plans $5 billion investment in Indian healthcare | publisher=Business Today | accessdate=25 August 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825084836/https://www.businesstoday.in/current/corporate/jang-sangh-hand-billionaire-b-r-shetty-5-billion-dollar-investments-in-indian-healthcare/story/373353.html | archive-date=25 August 2019 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2020, [[Bloomberg News]] report casted doubts on his real holding amidst the short-selling of NMC Health by [[Muddy Waters Research]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/international/business/a-jet-setting-billionaire-had-it-all-then-carson-block-came-along/articleshow/74204580.cms|title=Jet-setting billionaire Bavaguthu Raghuram Shetty had it all. Then Carson Block came along| publisher=Bloomberg| accessdate= 20 February 2020}}</ref> Also in February 2020, Shetty was ousted from the NMC Health board following a corporate governance scandal over his holdings in the company.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Correspondent|first=Ben Martin, Senior City|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nmcs-founder-forced-out-over-shares-scandal-cr59jz2s6|title=NMC's founder forced out over shares scandal|access-date=2020-02-25|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nOn April 8, 2020, NMC went into Administration in UK due to the insolvency of the company due to alleged frauds committed by Shetty.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/nmc-insolvency-proceedings-inevitable-hospital-143125949.html|title=NMC Heads to Administration After Giving In to Creditor Demands|website=finance.yahoo.com}}</ref>\n\n==Other activities==\nShetty has invested in a medical institution in the north Indian state of Uttarakhand. He is the founder and patron of the Indian Pharmaceutical Association in the Emirates, and is a member of the Advisory Board (Financial Sector), Economic Department, Government of Dubai, UAE and the Pharmaceutical Committee, Dubai. He is also the chairman of [[Abu Dhabi Indian School]] and Bright Riders School.<ref name=\"Indian tycoons storm Arabian Business Expat Power List 2011 - ArabianBusiness.com\">{{cite web | url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-tycoons-storm-arabian-business-expat-power-list-2011-383132.html#.V3JKfbh9600 | title=Indian tycoons storm Arabian Business Expat Power List 2011 - ArabianBusiness.com | publisher=ArabianBusiness | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160815070908/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/indian-tycoons-storm-arabian-business-expat-power-list-2011-383132.html#.V3JKfbh9600 | archive-date=15 August 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://brightriders.ae/?page_id=176|title=Chairman's Message {{!}} Bright Riders School, Abu Dhabi|website=brightriders.ae|language=en-US|access-date=2017-08-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170802164450/http://brightriders.ae/?page_id=176|archive-date=2 August 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2015, Shetty was elected as the Chairman to the board of directors of UAE Exchange.<ref name=khal>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/dr-br-shetty-takes-over-as-chairman-of-uae-exchange|title=Dr B.R. Shetty takes over as chairman of UAE Exchange|work=Khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085905/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/dr-br-shetty-takes-over-as-chairman-of-uae-exchange|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uae-exchange-appoints-b-r-shetty-as-chairman-promoth-manghat-as-ceo/articleshow/48652739.cms|title=UAE Exchange appoints B R Shetty as Chairman, Promoth Manghat as CEO|newspaper=The Economic Times|date=24 August 2015|publisher=Economic Times India|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424090633/http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/markets/stocks/news/uae-exchange-appoints-b-r-shetty-as-chairman-promoth-manghat-as-ceo/articleshow/48652739.cms|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> He was named chairman of The Indian Business/Professional Group in June 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/dr-b-r-shetty-to-head-the-indian-businessprofessional-group|title=Dr B R Shetty to head The Indian Business/Professional Group|publisher=News Karnataka|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085646/http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/dr-b-r-shetty-to-head-the-indian-businessprofessional-group|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> H. H. Sheikh Mohammed bin Rashid al Maktoum nominated Shetty as a member of the UAE medical council in September 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://m.bfirst.in/news/2016_09_09/12860|title=Businessman BR Shetty nominated to medical council by PM of Dubai|publisher=Bfirst}}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2017, Shetty announced that he would invest Rs 1000 crore ($157.3 million) to produce a film with director [[V. A. Shrikumar Menon]]. The film, starring [[Mohanlal]], was to be based on the novel [[Randamoozham]], a retelling of [[Mahabharata]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Billionaire B. R. Shetty aims for $1 billion in revenue from Indian film epic|url=https://in.reuters.com/article/nmc-health-shetty-film/billionaire-b-r-shetty-aims-for-1-billion-in-revenue-from-indian-film-epic-idINKBN18V0SR|access-date=28 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171027181423/https://in.reuters.com/article/nmc-health-shetty-film/billionaire-b-r-shetty-aims-for-1-billion-in-revenue-from-indian-film-epic-idINKBN18V0SR|archive-date=27 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\nIn May 2019, however, the film was shelved due to creative issues.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mohanlal's Rs 1000 crore film project 'Randamoozham' shelved|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2019/apr/03/mohanlals-rs-1000-crore-film-project-randamoozham-shelved-1959795.html|access-date=20 February 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805223955/http://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/malayalam/2019/apr/03/mohanlals-rs-1000-crore-film-project-randamoozham-shelved-1959795.html|archive-date=5 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognition ==\n{{Overly detailed|Section|date=February 2020}}\nIn 2005, Shetty was awarded the highest civilian distinction in the Emirate, the [[Abu Dhabi Awards]].<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty-1.119120 | title = Abu Dhabi Awards: B R Shetty | date = 23 May 2015 | work = The National | access-date = 23 September 2019 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190923071607/https://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty-1.119120 | archive-date = 23 September 2019 | url-status = live }}</ref> Given by H. H. Sheikh [[Mohammed bin Zayed Al Nahyan]], the Crown Prince of Abu Dhabi, the first year the distinction was awarded.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty|title=Abu Dhabi Awards: B R Shetty|publisher=The National|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170422235344/http://www.thenational.ae/uae/abu-dhabi-awards-b-r-shetty|archive-date=22 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Also in 2005, U.S. India Friendship Society presented Shetty the Distinguished Entrepreneur Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.neopharmauae.com/en/news.asp?News_Id=173-Dr.-B.R.-Shetty-received-The-Distinguished-Entrepreneur-Award-from-the-US-India-Friendship-Society-|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty received The Distinguished Entrepreneur Award from the US India Friendship Society|publisher=Neopharma|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173745/http://www.neopharmauae.com/en/news.asp?News_Id=173-Dr.-B.R.-Shetty-received-The-Distinguished-Entrepreneur-Award-from-the-US-India-Friendship-Society-|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref>\n\nShetty was honoured by the [[Pravasi Bharatiya Samman]] in 2007.<ref name=\"The recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman - Times of India\">{{cite web | url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/The-recipients-of-Pravasi-Bharatiya-Samman/articleshow/1113368.cms | title=The recipients of Pravasi Bharatiya Samman \u2013 Times of India | work=Times of India| accessdate=28 June 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"New Delhi B R Shetty Among Padma Shree Awardees\">{{cite web | url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=56080 | title=New Delhi B R Shetty Among Padma Shree Awardees | publisher=Daijiworld Media Pvt Ltd Mangalore | accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303170744/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/news_disp.asp?n_id=56080 | archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nErnst & Young Middle East honored Shetty with the Entrepreneur of the year finalist award in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emirates247.com/eb247/companies-markets/five-uae-execs-in-running-for-ernst-young-award-2008-01-17-1.216304|title=Five UAE execs in running for Ernst & Young award|publisher=Emirates 24/7|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085817/http://www.emirates247.com/eb247/companies-markets/five-uae-execs-in-running-for-ernst-young-award-2008-01-17-1.216304|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty received the [[Padma Shri|Padmashree]] awarded by the [[President of India]] in 2009 for his contribution in the field of trade and industry.<ref name=\"IBPC Felicitates Padma Shri Award Winners - Khaleej Times\">{{cite web | url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/ibpc-felicitates-padma-shri-award-winners | title=IBPC Felicitates Padma Shri Award Winners \u2013 Khaleej Times | work=Khaleej Times| accessdate=28 June 2016 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160808123305/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/ibpc-felicitates-padma-shri-award-winners | archive-date=8 August 2016 |url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, he received the Asian Achievers Award from the Human Achievers Foundation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/article/20110713/ARTICLE/307139999/1002|title=Asian Achievers Awards for Dhahi Khalfan, others|work=Khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174100/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/article/20110713/ARTICLE/307139999/1002|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2012, Pharma Leaders founded by Satya Brahma declared Shetty as Global Indian of the Year along with [[Kiran Mazumdar-Shaw|Kiran Mazumdar Shaw]] at 5th Annual Pharmaceutical Leadership Summit & Pharma Leaders Business Leadership Awards 2012 in Mumbai.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://pharmaleaders.tv/biocon-chief-dr-kiran-majumdar-shaw-nmc-chief-dr-b-r-shetty-declared-global-indian-of-the-year-2/|title=Biocon Chief Dr. Kiran Majumdar Shaw & NMC Chief Dr B.R.Shetty Declared Global Indian of the Year {{!}} Pharmaleaders TV|website=pharmaleaders.tv|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171024205347/http://pharmaleaders.tv/biocon-chief-dr-kiran-majumdar-shaw-nmc-chief-dr-b-r-shetty-declared-global-indian-of-the-year-2/|archive-date=24 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Shetty was recognized as one of Asia's most promising leaders at the Asian Brand & Leadership Summit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=189157|title=UAE Exchange named leader, most promising brand in Asia|publisher=Daiji World|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085721/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=189157|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In March 2013, he was awarded the International Achievers Summit's Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty receives Lifetime Achievement Award|publisher=NMC Trading|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174516/http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, Shetty received the Asian Business Leadership Forum India-UAE Business Icons Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ablfawards.com/2013-winners/|title=ABLF Awards 2013 Winners|publisher=ABLF|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161211033716/http://www.ablfawards.com/2013-winners/|archive-date=11 December 2016|url-status = dead}}</ref> He also received the 2013 Frost & Sullivan Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.frost.com/prod/servlet/press-release.pag?docid=291322634|title=Dr. B R Shetty honoured with Frost & Sullivan - Lifetime Achievement Award for the Year 2013|publisher=Frost & Sullivan|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170425031103/https://www.frost.com/prod/servlet/press-release.pag?docid=291322634|archive-date=25 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Forbes Middle East recognized Shetty with the Top Indian Leaders in the UAE Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbesmiddleeast.com/forbes-middle-east-unveils-top-indian-leaders-in-the-arab-region|title=Forbes Middle East Reveals Top Indian Leaders in the Arab World|website=Forbes Middle East|publisher=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> He also received the Lakshya Business Visionary Award in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/getahead/report/achievers-from-salesman-to-biz-tycoon-a-serial-entrepreneurs-success-mantras/20141105.htm|title=From salesman to biz tycoon: A serial entrepreneur's success mantras|publisher=Rediff|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173734/http://www.rediff.com/getahead/report/achievers-from-salesman-to-biz-tycoon-a-serial-entrepreneurs-success-mantras/20141105.htm|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, Shetty was recognized with the International Achievement Award at the Indian Innovator Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/entmagazineme/docs/entrepreneur_middle_east_january_20|title=Indian Innovator Awards 2014|publisher=Entrepreneur Middle East|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173725/https://issuu.com/entmagazineme/docs/entrepreneur_middle_east_january_20|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2015, the Indian Club - Bahrain recognized Shetty with a Centenary Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=295424|title=Bahrain : Dr Kalam presents Indian Club Centenary awards to Colaco, B R Shetty|publisher=Daiji World|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085429/http://www.daijiworld.com/news/newsDisplay.aspx?newsID=295424|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> He received the Deal of the Year Award at the 2015 Indian CEO Awards.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arabianbusiness.com/sunil-vaswani-takes-top-honours-at-indian-ceo-awards-582410.html|title=Sunil Vaswani takes top honours at Indian CEO Awards|publisher=Arabian Business|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171008135040/http://www.arabianbusiness.com/sunil-vaswani-takes-top-honours-at-indian-ceo-awards-582410.html|archive-date=8 October 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In June 2015, Shetty received the Business Personality of the Year award from Crowe Horwath International.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-has-received-the-prestigious-business-personality-of-the-year-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty has received the prestigious Business Personality of the Year award|publisher=NMV Health|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150805020024/http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-has-received-the-prestigious-business-personality-of-the-year-award/|archive-date=5 August 2015|url-status = dead}}</ref> That same month, Shetty received the Arabian Indian Czars award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-06-18/news/63567767_1_fadnavis-sunil-vaswani-rizwan-sajan|title=Arabian Indian Czars Award: Times Now felicitates successful Indians in Middle East|work=The Economic Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151018060431/http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-06-18/news/63567767_1_fadnavis-sunil-vaswani-rizwan-sajan|archive-date=18 October 2015|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nShetty received the Global Indian Achiever Award in 2015 from H. H. Sheikh Nahyan Bin Mubarak al Nahyan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-global-indian-achiever-award/|title=Dr. B R Shetty honoured with Global Indian Achiever Award|publisher=NMC Health|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171031042109/http://www.nmchealth.com/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-global-indian-achiever-award/|archive-date=31 October 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Also in 2015, H. H. Prince Faisal Bin Saud Bin Musaed Bin Abdulaziz presented Shetty with the National Cultural Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sauress.com/en/saudigazette/240107|title=Indian tycoon Shetty is honored with National Cultural Award|work=The Saudi Gazette|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173839/http://www.sauress.com/en/saudigazette/240107|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Shetty's company, NMC Healthcare, received the Frost & Sullivan Middle East Integrated Healthcare Company of the Year Award in 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfinance.com/infrastructure-investment/nmc-guides-the-way-for-the-uaes-healthcare-sector|title=NMC guides the way for the UAE's healthcare sector|publisher=World Finance|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170430214825/http://www.worldfinance.com/infrastructure-investment/nmc-guides-the-way-for-the-uaes-healthcare-sector|archive-date=30 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> That same year, MILAAP honored Shetty with a Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award-3/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty receives Lifetime Achievement Award|publisher=NMC Trading|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174031/http://www.nmctrading.com/dr-b-r-shetty-receives-lifetime-achievement-award-3/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nAt the 2015 Gulf Business Industry Awards, Shetty was recognized as the Healthcare Business Leader of the Year.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gulfbusiness.com/gulf-business-industry-awards-2015-business-leaders-year/|title=Gulf Business Industry Awards 2015: Business Leaders of the Year|date=9 September 2015|publisher=Gulf Business|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173736/http://gulfbusiness.com/gulf-business-industry-awards-2015-business-leaders-year/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> In November 2015, he was felicitated by More Ignatius Jacobite Syrian Orthodox Cathedral in Dubai.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brshetty.com/awards/dr-b-r-shetty-felicitated-by-mor-ignatius-jacobite-syrian-orthodox-cathedral/|title=Dr. B.R.Setty Felicitated By Mor Ignatius Jacobite Syrian Orthodox Cathedral, Dubai|publisher=Dr. B. R. Shetty|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424175818/http://www.brshetty.com/awards/dr-b-r-shetty-felicitated-by-mor-ignatius-jacobite-syrian-orthodox-cathedral/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Shetty's NMC Healthcare was recognized at the 6th Middle East Business Leaders Awards in 2015, where Shetty was given the Industry Excellence in Healthcare Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/mebla-honours-industry-leaders|title=Mebla honours industry leaders|work=khaleej Times|access-date=23 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085800/http://www.khaleejtimes.com/business/local/mebla-honours-industry-leaders|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Shetty received the Golden Peacock Lifetime Achievement Award for Business Leadership.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goldenpeacockaward.com/past-winners/individual-leadership-awards.html|title=Roll of Honour|publisher=Golden Peacock Awards|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424173821/http://www.goldenpeacockaward.com/past-winners/individual-leadership-awards.html|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> Also in 2016, Shetty won the Business Excellence Award from the Indian Business & Professional Council.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nmchealth.com/news/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-with-business-excellence-award/|title=Dr. B.R. Shetty honoured with Business Excellence Award|publisher=NMC Health|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085934/http://www.nmchealth.com/news/dr-b-r-shetty-honoured-with-business-excellence-award/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = dead}}</ref> Middlesex University in Dubai awarded Shetty an Honorary Doctorate in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mdx.ac.ae/about-us/honorary-doctorates|title=Middlesex Dubai Honorary Graduates|publisher=Middlesex University Dubai|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174731/http://www.mdx.ac.ae/about-us/honorary-doctorates|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2017, Shetty was honored at the Annual Health Awards with a special award for his contribution to the region's healthcare industry.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://article.wn.com/view/2017/01/23/Dr_B_R_Shetty_honoured_at_the_Annual_Health_Awards_2017_NMC_/|title=Dr. B. R. Shetty honoured at the Annual Health Awards 2017 (NMC Health plc)|publisher=World News|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424085508/https://article.wn.com/view/2017/01/23/Dr_B_R_Shetty_honoured_at_the_Annual_Health_Awards_2017_NMC_/|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref> The following month, Shetty received the Nadaprabhu Kempegowda International Award at the Kempegowda International Festival.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/kempegowda-international-festival-lays-emphasis-on-uniting-okkaligas-under-roof|title=Kempegowda International Festival lays emphasis on uniting Okkaligas under roof|publisher=News Karnataka|access-date=24 April 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170424174146/http://www.newskarnataka.com/nri/kempegowda-international-festival-lays-emphasis-on-uniting-okkaligas-under-roof|archive-date=24 April 2017|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018 Shetty was recognized by Forbes Middle East among the top Indian leaders in the Arab world.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gulfnews.com/business/revealed-top-indian-business-leaders-in-arab-world-1.2218991|title=Revealed: Top Indian business leaders in Arab world|publisher=Gulf News Business|accessdate=25 August 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190527090500/https://gulfnews.com/business/revealed-top-indian-business-leaders-in-arab-world-1.2218991|archive-date=27 May 2019|url-status = live}}</ref> In September 2018 Shetty received the C3 Lifetime Achievement Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/c3-us-arab-healthcare--business-summit-and-title-sponsor-alitheia-holdings-honors-keynote-speaker-dr-br-shetty-with-lifetime-achievement-award-300714982.html|publisher=PR Newswire|accessdate=25 August 2019|title=C3 US-Arab Healthcare & Business Summit and Title Sponsor Alitheia Holdings Honors Keynote Speaker Dr. B.R. Shetty with Lifetime Achievement Award|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190825020538/https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/c3-us-arab-healthcare--business-summit-and-title-sponsor-alitheia-holdings-honors-keynote-speaker-dr-br-shetty-with-lifetime-achievement-award-300714982.html|archive-date=25 August 2019|url-status = live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.brshetty.com/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Shetty, B. R.}}\n[[Category:Indian philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Mangaloreans]]\n[[Category:Tulu people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Shri in trade and industry]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Udupi district]]\n[[Category:Indian billionaires]]\n[[Category:Indian emigrants to the United Arab Emirates]]\n[[Category:1942 births]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from Karnataka]]\n[[Category:Giving Pledgers]]\n[[Category:21st-century philanthropists]]\n[[Category:Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:20th-century Indian businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian businesspeople]]\n", "name_user": "CharlestonMaani", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/B._R._Shetty"}
{"title_page": "George Washington's Farewell Address", "text_new": "{{use American English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox book|italic title=no\n| name       = Washington's Farewell Address\n| title_orig = The Address of Gen. Washington to the People of America on His Declining the Presidency of the United States\n| image      = Washington's_Farewell_Address.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| author     = George Washington with Alexander Hamilton (1796) and James Madison (1792)\n| pub_date   =  September 1796\n| publisher  = [[Pennsylvania Packet|American Daily Advertiser]]\n| Wikisource = Washington's Farewell Address\n}}\n{{WashingtonSeries}}\n\n'''George Washington's farewell address''' is a letter written by President [[George Washington]] as a [[valedictory]] to \"friends and fellow-citizens\" after 20 years of public service to the United States.<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\">{{cite wikisource |first=George |last=Washington |authorlink=George Washington |date=September 17, 1796 |title=Washington's Farewell Address}}</ref> He wrote it near the end of his second term of [[Presidency of George Washington|presidency]] before retiring to his home at [[Mount Vernon]] in Virginia.\n\nThe letter was first published as '''''The Address of Gen. Washington to the Men of America on His inclining the Presidency of the United States''''' in the ''[[Pennsylvania Packet|American Daily Advertiser]]'' on September 19, 1796, about ten weeks before the presidential electors cast their votes in the [[1796 United States presidential election|1796 election]]. It is a classic statement of [[Republicanism in the United States|republicanism]],<ref>igoogle.com/search?q=kirishima&safe=strict&sxsrf=ACYBGNTRGJtUwrEUzk4oi146Ew2EyGQ5PA:1579136665772&source=lnms&tbm=isch&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimj4_A9obnAhVLba0KHXMcA_8Q_AUoAXoECA8QAw&biw=1366&bih=641#imgrc=0ihsiPWqfn00dM:</ref> warning Americans of the political dangers which they must avoid if they are to remain true to their values. It was almost immediately reprinted in newspapers throughout the country, and later in pamphlet form.<ref name=\"loc.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/religion/rel06.html |title=Religion and the Founding of the American Republic |publisher=Loc.gov |date=October 27, 2003 |accessdate=September 19, 2009}}{{LOC-general}}</ref>\n\nThe first draft was originally prepared by [[James Madison]] in June 1792, as Washington contemplated retiring at the end of his first term in office.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gwpapers.virginia.edu/documents/washingtons-farewell-address/| title=Washington's Farewell Address| publisher=Papers of George Washington| location=University of Virginia, Charlottesville, Virginia| accessdate=August 4, 2017}}</ref> However, he set it aside and ran for a second term because of heated disputes between Secretary of the Treasury [[Alexander Hamilton]] and Secretary of State [[Thomas Jefferson]] which convinced Washington that the growing tensions would rip apart the country without his leadership. This included the state of foreign affairs, and divisions between the newly formed [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] and [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] parties.<ref name=\"E&M1995\">{{cite book| first1=Stanley| last1=Elkins| first2=Eric| last2=McKitrick| title=The Age of Federalism: The Early American Republic, 1788-1800| publisher=Oxford University Press| date=1995| pages=489\u2013499| isbn=978-0-19-509381-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9RyG29bER3QC&pg=PA489}}</ref>\n\nAs his second term came to a close four years later, Washington prepared a revision of the original letter with the help of Hamilton to write a new farewell address to announce his intention to decline a third term in office. He reflects on the emerging issues of the American political landscape in 1796, expresses his support for the government eight years after the adoption of the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]], defends his administration's record and gives valedictory advice to the American people.<ref name=\"Farewell Address\"/>\n\n== Summary ==\n[[File:Washington (3).jpg|thumb|Portrait of [[George Washington]] by [[Gilbert Stuart]]]]\nThe thought of the United States without George Washington as its president caused concern among many Americans. [[Thomas Jefferson]] disagreed with many of the president's policies and later led the Democratic-Republicans in opposition to many Federalist policies, but he joined his political rival [[Alexander Hamilton]]\u2014the leader of the Federalists\u2014in convincing the president to delay his retirement and serve a second term. The two men feared that the nation would be torn apart without his leadership. Washington most likely referred to this when he told the American people that he had wanted to retire before the last election, but he was convinced by people who were, in his words, \"entitled to my confidence\" that it was his duty to serve a second term.<ref name=\"E&M1995\"/> All of the ideas presented in Washington's Farewell Address came from Washington; however, Alexander Hamilton wrote most of it.<ref name=\"Primary Documents in American History\">{{cite web|title=George Washington's Farewell Address: Primary Documents of American History (Virtual Programs & Services, Library of Congress)|url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/program/bib/ourdocs/farewell.html|date=September 6, 2017|website=Library of Congress|accessdate=February 26, 2017|ref=9}}</ref>\n\nWashington sought to convince the American people that his service was no longer necessary by telling them, as he had in his first inaugural address, that he truly believed that he was never qualified to be president. If he accomplished anything during his presidency, he said, it was as a result of their support and efforts to help the country survive and prosper. Despite his confidence that the country would survive without his leadership, Washington used the majority of the letter to offer advice as a \"parting friend\" on what he believed were the greatest threats to the nation.<ref name=\"E&M1995\"/>\n\n=== Unity and sectionalism ===\nThe Address expresses Washington's understanding of republicanism by affirming popular government and warning about threats to \"Republican liberty\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert W. Watson|title=White House Studies Compendium|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I_0cTQo8t7oC&pg=PA319|year=2007|publisher=Nova Publishers|page=319}}</ref> He begins his warnings to the American people by stressing that their independence, peace at home and abroad, safety, prosperity, and liberty are all dependent upon unity among the states. He warns them that the union of states created by the Constitution will come under the most frequent and focused attacks by foreign and domestic enemies of the country. He warns the American people to be suspicious of anyone who seeks to abandon the Union, to secede a portion of the country from the rest, or to weaken the bonds that hold together the constitutional union. To promote the strength of the Union, he urges the people to place their identity as Americans above their identities as members of a state, city, or region, and to focus their efforts and affection on the country above all other local interests. He reminds the people that they do not have more than slight differences in religion, manners, habits, and political principles, and that their triumph and possession of independence and liberty are the result of working together.<ref name=\"E&M1995\"/>\n\nWashington continues to express his support of the Union by giving some examples of how he believes that the country, its regions, and its people are already benefiting from the unity which they currently share. He then looks to the future in his belief that the combined effort and resources of its people will protect the country from foreign attack and allow them to avoid wars between neighboring nations that often happen due to rivalries and competing relations with foreign nations. He argues that the security provided by the Union will also allow the United States to avoid the creation of an overgrown military which he sees as a great threat to liberty, especially the republican liberty which the United States has created.\n\nWashington goes on to warn the American people to question the ulterior motives of any person or group who argues that the land within the borders of the United States is too large to be ruled as a republic, an argument made by many during the debate on the proposed purchase of the [[Louisiana Territory]], calling on the people to give the experiment of a large republic a chance to work before deciding that it cannot be done. He then offers strong warnings on the dangers of [[sectionalism]], arguing that the true motives of a sectionalist are to create distrust or rivalries between regions and people to gain power and take control of the government. Washington points to the [[Jay Treaty]] and [[Pinckney's Treaty]] which established the borders of the United States' western territories between Spanish Mexico and British Canada, and secured the rights of western farmers to ship goods along the [[Mississippi River]] to New Orleans. He holds up these treaties as proof that the eastern states along the Atlantic Coast and the federal government are looking out for the welfare of all the American people and can win fair treatment from foreign countries as a united nation.<ref name=\"E&M1995\"/>\n\n=== Constitution and political factions ===\n[[File: Thomas Jefferson by Rembrandt Peale, 1800.jpg|thumb|[[Thomas Jefferson]], the founder of the [[Democratic-Republican Party]]]]\nWashington goes on to state his support for the new constitutional government, calling it an improvement upon the nation's original attempt in the [[Articles of Confederation]]. He reminds the people that it is the [[Right of revolution|right of the people to alter the government]] to meet their needs, but it should only be done through constitutional amendments. He reinforces this belief by arguing that violent takeovers of the government should be avoided at all costs and that it is the duty of every member of the republic to follow the constitution and to submit to the laws of the government until it is constitutionally amended by the majority of the American people.<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\">{{cite wikisource |first=George |last=Washington |authorlink=George Washington |date=September 17, 1796 |title=Washington's Farewell Address}}</ref>\n\nWashington warns the people that political factions may seek to obstruct the execution of the laws created by the government or to prevent the branches of government from enacting the powers provided them by the constitution. Such factions may claim to be trying to answer popular demands or solve pressing problems, but their true intentions are to take the power from the people and place it in the hands of unjust men.<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\"/>\n\nWashington calls the American people to only change the Constitution through amendments, but he then warns them that groups seeking to overthrow the government may strive to pass constitutional amendments to weaken the government to a point where it is unable to defend itself from political factions, enforce its laws, and protect the people's rights and property. As a result, he urges them to give the government time to realize its full potential, and only amend the constitution after thorough time and thought have proven that it is truly necessary instead of simply making changes based upon opinions and hypotheses of the moment.<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\"/>\n\n=== Political parties ===\n[[File: Alexander Hamilton portrait by John Trumbull 1806.jpg|thumb|[[Alexander Hamilton]], the founder of the [[Federalist Party]]]]\nWashington continues to advance his idea of the dangers of sectionalism and expands his warning to include the dangers of political parties to the country as a whole. These warnings are given in the context of the recent rise of two opposing parties within the government\u2014the [[Democratic-Republican Party]] led by Jefferson, and Hamilton's [[Federalist Party]]. Washington had striven to remain neutral during a conflict between Britain and France brought about by the [[French Revolution]], while the Democratic-Republicans had made efforts to align with France, and the Federalists had made efforts to ally with Great Britain.\n\nWashington recognizes that it is natural for people to organize and operate within groups such as political parties, but he also argues that every government has recognized political parties as an enemy and has sought to repress them because of their tendency to seek more power than other groups and to take revenge on political opponents.<ref name=\"E&M1995\"/> He feels that disagreements between political parties weakened the government.\n\nMoreover, he makes the case that \"the alternate domination\" of one party over another and coinciding efforts to exact revenge upon their opponents have led to horrible atrocities, and \"is itself a frightful despotism. But this leads at length to a more formal and permanent despotism.\"  From Washington's perspective and judgment, political parties eventually and \"gradually incline the minds of men to seek security\u2026 in the absolute power of an individual\",<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\"/> leading to despotism. He acknowledges the fact that parties are sometimes beneficial in promoting liberty in monarchies, but he argues that political parties must be restrained in a popularly elected government because of their tendency to distract the government from their duties, create unfounded jealousies among groups and regions, raise false alarms among the people, promote riots and insurrection, and provide foreign nations and interests access to the government where they can impose their will upon the country.\n\n=== Checks and balances and separation of powers ===\nWashington continues his defense of the Constitution by stating that the system of [[Separation of powers#Checks and balances|checks and balances]] and [[Separation of powers under the United States Constitution|separation of powers]] within it are important means of preventing a single person or group from seizing control of the country. He advises the American people that, if they believe that it is necessary to modify the powers granted to the government through the Constitution, it should be done through constitutional amendments instead of through force.\n\n[[File:Valley Forge prayer.jpg|thumb|This 1866 engraving depicts Washington praying at [[Valley Forge]]]]\n\n=== Religion, morality and education ===\nOne of the most referenced parts of Washington's letter is his strong support of the importance of religion and morality in promoting private and public happiness and in promoting the political prosperity of the nation.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} He argues that religious principles promote the protection of property, reputation, and life that are the foundations of justice. He cautions against the belief that the nation's morality can be maintained without religion:\n{{quote|Of all the dispositions and habits which lead to political prosperity, religion, and morality are indispensable supports. In vain would that man claim the tribute of patriotism, who should labor to subvert these great pillars of human happiness, these firmest props of the duties of men and citizens. The mere politician, equally with the pious man, ought to respect and to cherish them. A volume could not trace all their connections with private and public felicity. Let it simply be asked: Where is the security for property, for reputation, for life, if the sense of religious obligation desert the oaths which are the instruments of investigation in courts of justice? And let us with caution indulge the supposition that morality can be maintained without religion. Whatever may be conceded to the influence of refined education on minds of peculiar structure, reason and experience both forbid us to expect that national morality can prevail in exclusion of religious principle.<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\"/>}}\n\nWashington refers to religious principle as the foundation of public morality.  He also argues that the American government needs to ensure \"the general diffusion of knowledge\"<ref name=\"Farewell Address\" /> throughout the United States; the government has been created to enforce the opinion of the people, so the opinion of the people should be informed and knowledgeable.\n\n=== Credit and government attacking ===\nWashington provides strong support for a balanced federal budget, arguing that the nation's credit is an important source of strength and security. He urges the American people to preserve the national credit by avoiding war, avoiding unnecessary borrowing, and paying off any national debt accumulated in times of war as quickly as possible in times of peace so that future generations do not have to take on the financial burdens. Despite his warnings to avoid taking on debt, Washington does state his belief that sometimes it is necessary to spend money to prevent dangers or wars that will cost more if not properly prepared for. At these times, he argues, it is necessary for the people to cooperate by paying taxes to cover these precautionary expenses. He emphasizes how important it is for the government to be careful in choosing the items that will be taxed, but also reminds the American people that, no matter how hard the government tries, there will never be a tax which is not inconvenient and unpleasant to those who must pay it.\n\n=== Foreign relations and free trade ===\nWashington dedicates a large part of his farewell address to discussing foreign relations and the dangers of permanent alliances between the United States and foreign nations, which he views as foreign entanglements.<ref>{{cite journal| first=Samuel Flagg| last=Bemis| title=Washington's Farewell Address: A Foreign Policy of Independence| journal=American Historical Review| date=1934| volume=39| issue=2| pages=250\u2013268| jstor=1838722}}</ref> He advocates a policy of good faith and justice towards all nations, again making reference to proper behavior based upon religious doctrine and morality. He urges the American people to avoid long-term friendly relations or rivalries with any nation, arguing that attachments with or animosity toward other nations will only cloud the government's judgment in its foreign policy. He argues that longstanding poor relations will only lead to unnecessary wars due to a tendency to blow minor offenses out of proportion when committed by nations viewed as enemies of the United States. He continues this argument by claiming that alliances are likely to draw the United States into wars that have no justification and no benefit to the country beyond simply defending the favored nation. Alliances, he warns, often lead to poor relations with nations who feel that they are not being treated as well as America's allies, and threaten to influence the American government into making decisions based upon the will of their allies instead of the will of the American people.\n[[Image:Edmond-Charles Gen\u00eat.png|thumb|right|150px|[[Edmond-Charles Gen\u00eat|Citizen Gen\u00eat]] was the French minister who interfered in U.S. politics]]\n\nWashington makes an extended reference to the dangers of foreign nations who will seek to influence the American people and government; nations who may be considered friendly as well as nations considered enemies will equally try to influence the government to do their will. \"Real patriots\", he warns, who \"resist the intrigues\" of foreign nations may find themselves \"suspected and odious\" in the eyes of others, yet he urges the people to stand firm against such influences all the same. He portrays those who attempt to further such foreign interests as becoming the \"tools and dupes\" of those nations, stealing the applause and praise of their country away from the \"real patriots\" while actually working to \"surrender\" American interests to foreign nations.\n\nWashington goes on to urge the American people to take advantage of their isolated position in the world, and to avoid attachments and entanglements in foreign affairs, especially those of Europe, which he argues have little or nothing to do with the interests of America. He argues that it makes no sense for the American people to become embroiled in European affairs when their isolated position and unity allow them to remain neutral and focus on their own affairs. He argues that the country should avoid permanent alliances with all foreign nations, although temporary alliances during times of extreme danger may be necessary. He states that current treaties should be honored but not extended.\n\nWashington wraps up his foreign policy stance by advocating free trade with all nations, arguing that trade links should be established naturally and the role of the government should be limited to ensuring stable trade, defending the rights of American merchants and any provisions necessary to ensure the conventional rules of trade.\n\n=== Address's intentions ===\nWashington uses this portion of the address to explain that he does not expect his advice to make any great impression upon the people or to change the course of American politics, but he does hope that the people will remember his devoted service to his country.\n\n=== Defense of the Proclamation of Neutrality ===\nWashington then explains his reasoning behind the [[Proclamation of Neutrality]] which he made during the [[French Revolutionary Wars]], despite the standing [[Treaty of Alliance (1778)|Treaty of Alliance]] with France. He explains that the United States had a right to remain neutral in the conflict and that the correctness of that decision \"has been virtually admitted by all\" nations since. Justice and humanity required him to remain neutral during the conflict, he argues, and the neutrality was also necessary to allow the new government a chance to mature and gain enough strength to control its own affairs.\n\n=== Closing thoughts ===\nWashington closes his letter to the American people by asking them to forgive any failures which may have occurred during his service to the country, assuring them that they were due to his own weaknesses and by no means intentional. The sentences express his excitement about joining his fellow Americans as a private citizen in the free government which they have created together during his 45 years of public service.\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{see|Post-presidency of George Washington}}\nWashington's Farewell Address is considered to be one of the most important documents in American history<ref name=\"loc.gov\"/> and the foundation of the Federalist Party's political doctrine.\n\nWashington later accepted a commission from President [[John Adams]], despite his stated desire to retire from public service, as the [[Commanding General of the United States Army|Senior Officer]] of a Provisional Army formed to defend the nation against a possible invasion by French forces during the [[Quasi-War]].<ref name=\"mountvernon.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mountvernon.org/learn/meet_george/index.cfm/ss/21/ |title=A Brief Biography of George Washington |publisher=Mountvernon.org |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823160852/http://www.mountvernon.org/learn/meet_george/index.cfm/ss/21 |archivedate=August 23, 2011 }}</ref> Washington held true to his statements in his farewell address, despite spending months organizing the Officer Corps of the Provisional Army, and declined suggestions that he return to public office in the [[1800 United States presidential election|presidential election of 1800]].<ref name=\"mountvernon.org\"/>\n\nWashington's statements on the importance of religion and morality in American politics and his warnings on the dangers of foreign alliances influenced political debates into the twentieth century,<ref name=\"loc.gov\"/> and have received special consideration as advice from an American hero.\n\n=== Alliances with foreign nations ===\nWashington's hope that the United States would end permanent alliances with foreign nations was realized in 1800 with the [[Convention of 1800]], the Treaty of Mortefontaine which officially ended the 1778 Treaty of Alliance, in exchange for ending the Quasi-War and establishing [[Most favoured nation|most favored nation]] trade relations with [[First French Empire|Napoleonic France]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xenophongroup.com/mcjoynt/alliance2.htm |title=Perspective On The French-American Alliance |publisher=Xenophongroup.com |date= |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090120014620/http://xenophongroup.com/mcjoynt/alliance2.htm |archive-date=January 20, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1823, Washington's foreign policy goals were further realized in the [[Monroe Doctrine]], which promised non-interference in European affairs so long as the nations of Europe did not seek to colonize or interfere with the newly independent Latin American nations of Central and [[South America]]. The United States did not enter into any permanent military alliances with foreign nations until the 1949 [[North Atlantic Treaty]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/basictxt/treaty.htm |title=Online Library: North Atlantic Treaty Organization |publisher=Nato.int |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913210131/http://www.nato.int/docu/basictxt/treaty.htm |archivedate=September 13, 2008 }}</ref> which formed [[NATO]].\n\n=== Reading in Congress ===\n[[Philadelphia]] residents signed a petition in January 1862 during the [[American Civil War]] requesting that Congress commemorate the 130th anniversary of Washington's birth by reading his Farewell Address \"in one or the other of the Houses of Congress.\"<ref name=\"Farewell Address\">{{cite web |url=http://www.access.gpo.gov/congress/senate/farewell/sd106-21.pdf |title=Washington's Farewell Address, Senate Document No. 106\u201321, Washington, 2000 |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612002306/http://www.access.gpo.gov/congress/senate/farewell/sd106-21.pdf |archive-date=June 12, 2009 |url-status=dead }}{{Include-GPO}}</ref> It was first read in the House of Representatives in February 1862, and reading Washington's address became a tradition in both houses by 1899. The House of Representatives abandoned the practice in 1984,<ref name=\"Farewell Address\"/> but the Senate continues the tradition. [[Washington's Birthday]] is observed by selecting a member of the Senate to read the address aloud on the Senate floor, alternating between political parties each year since 1896.<ref name=\"Farewell Address\"/> Additionally, readers make an entry into a black, leather-bound journal maintained by the Secretary of the Senate upon finishing.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/minute/Washingtons_Farewell_Address.htm | title=U.S. Senate: Washington's Farewell Address | author=United States Senate}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nAccording to political journalist [[John Avlon]], the Farewell Address was \"once celebrated as a civic Scripture, more widely reprinted than the Declaration of Independence\" but adds that it \"is now almost forgotten.\"<ref>{{cite book|first=John |last=Avlon|authorlink=John Avlon|title=Washington's Farewell: The Founding Father's Warning to Future Generations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UGXUDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1|year=2017|publisher=Simon and Schuster|page=1}}</ref> He suggested that it had long been \"eclipsed in the national memory\" until the Broadway musical ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' brought it back to popular awareness in the song \"[[One Last Time (Hamilton)|One Last Time]]\", where lines are sung by Washington and Hamilton from the end of the Address.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/01/08/508537167/what-we-can-learn-from-washingtons-farewell|title=What We Can Learn From 'Washington's Farewell'|last=|first=|date=January 8, 2017|work=All Things Considered|access-date=|publisher=National Public Radio|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Federalist Era]] which covers the 1790s\n* [[Republicanism in the United States]]\n* [[United States non-interventionism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{main|Bibliography of George Washington}}\n* Avlon, John. ''Washington's Farewell: The Founding Father's Warning to Future Generations'' (2017) [https://www.amazon.com/dp/147674646X/  excerpt]\n* {{cite journal |last=DeConde |first=Alexander |title=Washington's Farewell, the French Alliance, and the Election of 1796 |journal=Mississippi Valley Historical Review |year=1957 |volume=43 |issue=4 |pages=641\u2013658 |issn=0161-391X |doi=10.2307/1902277}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gilbert |first=Felix |title=To the Farewell Address: Ideas of Early American Foreign Policy |year=1961 |location=New York |publisher=Harper and Row }}\n* Hostetler, Michael J. \"Washington's farewell address: Distance as bane and blessing\". ''Rhetoric & Public Affairs'' (2002) 5#3 pp: 393\u2013407. [http://mtw160-198.ippl.jhu.edu/journals/rhetoric_and_public_affairs/v005/5.3hostetler.pdf online]\n* Kaufman, Burton Ira, ed. (1969) ''Washington's Farewell Address: The View from the 20th Century'' (Quadrangle Books) essays by scholars\n* Malanson, Jeffrey J. (2015) ''Addressing America: George Washington's Farewell and the Making of National Culture, Politics, and Diplomacy, 1796\u20131852'' (Kent State University Press, 2015). x, 253 pp [https://www.amazon.com/Addressing-America-Washingtons-Diplomacy-1796-1852/dp/1606352512/ excerpt]\n* {{cite journal |last=Pessen |first=Edward |author-link=Edward Pessen |title=George Washington's Farewell Address, the Cold War, and the Timeless National |journal=Journal of the Early Republic |year=1987 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201327 |issn=0275-1275 |doi=10.2307/3123426}}\n* {{cite book |last=Spalding |first=Matthew |first2=Patrick J. |last2=Garrity |lastauthoramp=yes |title=A Sacred Union of Citizens: George Washington's Farewell Address and the American Character |location=Lanham, MD |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=1996 |isbn=0-8476-8261-7 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/sacredunionofcit00spal }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Spalding |first=Matthew |authormask=3 |title=George Washington's Farewell Address |journal=[[The Wilson Quarterly]] |volume=20 |issue=4 |year=1996 |pages= |doi= }}\n* {{cite book |last=Varg |first=Paul A. |title=Foreign Policies of the Founding Fathers |year=1963 |location=Baltimore |publisher=Penguin Books|URL=https://archive.org/details/foreignpolicieso00varg_0 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|George Washington}}\n* [https://www.loc.gov/item/mjm012832/  James Madison's manuscript of June 21 1792]\n* [https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/node/200675 Text of Washington's Farewell Address]\n\n{{George Washington}}\n{{Alexander Hamilton}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:1796 documents]]\n[[Category:1796 in politics]]\n[[Category:1796 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Farewell addresses]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Presidency of George Washington]]\n[[Category:Speeches by George Washington|Farewell Address]]\n", "text_old": "{{use American English|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox book|italic title=no\n| name       = Washington's Farewell Address\n| title_orig = The Address of Gen. Washington to the People of America on His Declining the Presidency of the United States\n| image      = Washington's_Farewell_Address.jpg\n| image_size = 250px\n| author     = George Washington with Alexander Hamilton (1796) and James Madison (1792)\n| pub_date   =  September 1796\n| publisher  = [[Pennsylvania Packet|American Daily Advertiser]]\n| Wikisource = Washington's Farewell Address\n}}\n{{WashingtonSeries}}\n\n'''George Washington's farewell address''' is a letter written by President [[George Washington]] as a [[valedictory]] to \"friends and fellow-citizens\" after 20 years of public service to the United States.<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\">{{cite wikisource |first=George |last=Washington |authorlink=George Washington |date=September 17, 1796 |title=Washington's Farewell Address}}</ref> He wrote it near the end of his second term of [[Presidency of George Washington|presidency]] before retiring to his home at [[Mount Vernon]] in Virginia.\n\nThe letter was first published as '''''The Address of Gen. Washington to the Men of America on His Declining the Presidency of the United States''''' in the ''[[Pennsylvania Packet|American Daily Advertiser]]'' on September 19, 1796, about ten weeks before the presidential electors cast their votes in the [[1796 United States presidential election|1796 election]]. It is a classic statement of [[Republicanism in the United States|republicanism]],<ref>igoogle.com/search?q=kirishima&safe=strict&sxsrf=ACYBGNTRGJtUwrEUzk4oi146Ew2EyGQ5PA:1579136665772&source=lnms&tbm=isch&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwimj4_A9obnAhVLba0KHXMcA_8Q_AUoAXoECA8QAw&biw=1366&bih=641#imgrc=0ihsiPWqfn00dM:</ref> warning Americans of the political dangers which they must avoid if they are to remain true to their values. It was almost immediately reprinted in newspapers throughout the country, and later in pamphlet form.<ref name=\"loc.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/exhibits/religion/rel06.html |title=Religion and the Founding of the American Republic |publisher=Loc.gov |date=October 27, 2003 |accessdate=September 19, 2009}}{{LOC-general}}</ref>\n\nThe first draft was originally prepared by [[James Madison]] in June 1792, as Washington contemplated retiring at the end of his first term in office.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://gwpapers.virginia.edu/documents/washingtons-farewell-address/| title=Washington's Farewell Address| publisher=Papers of George Washington| location=University of Virginia, Charlottesville, Virginia| accessdate=August 4, 2017}}</ref> However, he set it aside and ran for a second term because of heated disputes between Secretary of the Treasury [[Alexander Hamilton]] and Secretary of State [[Thomas Jefferson]] which convinced Washington that the growing tensions would rip apart the country without his leadership. This included the state of foreign affairs, and divisions between the newly formed [[Federalist Party|Federalist]] and [[Democratic-Republican Party|Democratic-Republican]] parties.<ref name=\"E&M1995\">{{cite book| first1=Stanley| last1=Elkins| first2=Eric| last2=McKitrick| title=The Age of Federalism: The Early American Republic, 1788-1800| publisher=Oxford University Press| date=1995| pages=489\u2013499| isbn=978-0-19-509381-0|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9RyG29bER3QC&pg=PA489}}</ref>\n\nAs his second term came to a close four years later, Washington prepared a revision of the original letter with the help of Hamilton to write a new farewell address to announce his intention to decline a third term in office. He reflects on the emerging issues of the American political landscape in 1796, expresses his support for the government eight years after the adoption of the [[United States Constitution|Constitution]], defends his administration's record and gives valedictory advice to the American people.<ref name=\"Farewell Address\"/>\n\n== Summary ==\n[[File:Washington (3).jpg|thumb|Portrait of [[George Washington]] by [[Gilbert Stuart]]]]\nThe thought of the United States without George Washington as its president caused concern among many Americans. [[Thomas Jefferson]] disagreed with many of the president's policies and later led the Democratic-Republicans in opposition to many Federalist policies, but he joined his political rival [[Alexander Hamilton]]\u2014the leader of the Federalists\u2014in convincing the president to delay his retirement and serve a second term. The two men feared that the nation would be torn apart without his leadership. Washington most likely referred to this when he told the American people that he had wanted to retire before the last election, but he was convinced by people who were, in his words, \"entitled to my confidence\" that it was his duty to serve a second term.<ref name=\"E&M1995\"/> All of the ideas presented in Washington's Farewell Address came from Washington; however, Alexander Hamilton wrote most of it.<ref name=\"Primary Documents in American History\">{{cite web|title=George Washington's Farewell Address: Primary Documents of American History (Virtual Programs & Services, Library of Congress)|url=https://www.loc.gov/rr/program/bib/ourdocs/farewell.html|date=September 6, 2017|website=Library of Congress|accessdate=February 26, 2017|ref=9}}</ref>\n\nWashington sought to convince the American people that his service was no longer necessary by telling them, as he had in his first inaugural address, that he truly believed that he was never qualified to be president. If he accomplished anything during his presidency, he said, it was as a result of their support and efforts to help the country survive and prosper. Despite his confidence that the country would survive without his leadership, Washington used the majority of the letter to offer advice as a \"parting friend\" on what he believed were the greatest threats to the nation.<ref name=\"E&M1995\"/>\n\n=== Unity and sectionalism ===\nThe Address expresses Washington's understanding of republicanism by affirming popular government and warning about threats to \"Republican liberty\".<ref>{{cite book|author=Robert W. Watson|title=White House Studies Compendium|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I_0cTQo8t7oC&pg=PA319|year=2007|publisher=Nova Publishers|page=319}}</ref> He begins his warnings to the American people by stressing that their independence, peace at home and abroad, safety, prosperity, and liberty are all dependent upon unity among the states. He warns them that the union of states created by the Constitution will come under the most frequent and focused attacks by foreign and domestic enemies of the country. He warns the American people to be suspicious of anyone who seeks to abandon the Union, to secede a portion of the country from the rest, or to weaken the bonds that hold together the constitutional union. To promote the strength of the Union, he urges the people to place their identity as Americans above their identities as members of a state, city, or region, and to focus their efforts and affection on the country above all other local interests. He reminds the people that they do not have more than slight differences in religion, manners, habits, and political principles, and that their triumph and possession of independence and liberty are the result of working together.<ref name=\"E&M1995\"/>\n\nWashington continues to express his support of the Union by giving some examples of how he believes that the country, its regions, and its people are already benefiting from the unity which they currently share. He then looks to the future in his belief that the combined effort and resources of its people will protect the country from foreign attack and allow them to avoid wars between neighboring nations that often happen due to rivalries and competing relations with foreign nations. He argues that the security provided by the Union will also allow the United States to avoid the creation of an overgrown military which he sees as a great threat to liberty, especially the republican liberty which the United States has created.\n\nWashington goes on to warn the American people to question the ulterior motives of any person or group who argues that the land within the borders of the United States is too large to be ruled as a republic, an argument made by many during the debate on the proposed purchase of the [[Louisiana Territory]], calling on the people to give the experiment of a large republic a chance to work before deciding that it cannot be done. He then offers strong warnings on the dangers of [[sectionalism]], arguing that the true motives of a sectionalist are to create distrust or rivalries between regions and people to gain power and take control of the government. Washington points to the [[Jay Treaty]] and [[Pinckney's Treaty]] which established the borders of the United States' western territories between Spanish Mexico and British Canada, and secured the rights of western farmers to ship goods along the [[Mississippi River]] to New Orleans. He holds up these treaties as proof that the eastern states along the Atlantic Coast and the federal government are looking out for the welfare of all the American people and can win fair treatment from foreign countries as a united nation.<ref name=\"E&M1995\"/>\n\n=== Constitution and political factions ===\n[[File: Thomas Jefferson by Rembrandt Peale, 1800.jpg|thumb|[[Thomas Jefferson]], the founder of the [[Democratic-Republican Party]]]]\nWashington goes on to state his support for the new constitutional government, calling it an improvement upon the nation's original attempt in the [[Articles of Confederation]]. He reminds the people that it is the [[Right of revolution|right of the people to alter the government]] to meet their needs, but it should only be done through constitutional amendments. He reinforces this belief by arguing that violent takeovers of the government should be avoided at all costs and that it is the duty of every member of the republic to follow the constitution and to submit to the laws of the government until it is constitutionally amended by the majority of the American people.<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\">{{cite wikisource |first=George |last=Washington |authorlink=George Washington |date=September 17, 1796 |title=Washington's Farewell Address}}</ref>\n\nWashington warns the people that political factions may seek to obstruct the execution of the laws created by the government or to prevent the branches of government from enacting the powers provided them by the constitution. Such factions may claim to be trying to answer popular demands or solve pressing problems, but their true intentions are to take the power from the people and place it in the hands of unjust men.<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\"/>\n\nWashington calls the American people to only change the Constitution through amendments, but he then warns them that groups seeking to overthrow the government may strive to pass constitutional amendments to weaken the government to a point where it is unable to defend itself from political factions, enforce its laws, and protect the people's rights and property. As a result, he urges them to give the government time to realize its full potential, and only amend the constitution after thorough time and thought have proven that it is truly necessary instead of simply making changes based upon opinions and hypotheses of the moment.<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\"/>\n\n=== Political parties ===\n[[File: Alexander Hamilton portrait by John Trumbull 1806.jpg|thumb|[[Alexander Hamilton]], the founder of the [[Federalist Party]]]]\nWashington continues to advance his idea of the dangers of sectionalism and expands his warning to include the dangers of political parties to the country as a whole. These warnings are given in the context of the recent rise of two opposing parties within the government\u2014the [[Democratic-Republican Party]] led by Jefferson, and Hamilton's [[Federalist Party]]. Washington had striven to remain neutral during a conflict between Britain and France brought about by the [[French Revolution]], while the Democratic-Republicans had made efforts to align with France, and the Federalists had made efforts to ally with Great Britain.\n\nWashington recognizes that it is natural for people to organize and operate within groups such as political parties, but he also argues that every government has recognized political parties as an enemy and has sought to repress them because of their tendency to seek more power than other groups and to take revenge on political opponents.<ref name=\"E&M1995\"/> He feels that disagreements between political parties weakened the government.\n\nMoreover, he makes the case that \"the alternate domination\" of one party over another and coinciding efforts to exact revenge upon their opponents have led to horrible atrocities, and \"is itself a frightful despotism. But this leads at length to a more formal and permanent despotism.\"  From Washington's perspective and judgment, political parties eventually and \"gradually incline the minds of men to seek security\u2026 in the absolute power of an individual\",<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\"/> leading to despotism. He acknowledges the fact that parties are sometimes beneficial in promoting liberty in monarchies, but he argues that political parties must be restrained in a popularly elected government because of their tendency to distract the government from their duties, create unfounded jealousies among groups and regions, raise false alarms among the people, promote riots and insurrection, and provide foreign nations and interests access to the government where they can impose their will upon the country.\n\n=== Checks and balances and separation of powers ===\nWashington continues his defense of the Constitution by stating that the system of [[Separation of powers#Checks and balances|checks and balances]] and [[Separation of powers under the United States Constitution|separation of powers]] within it are important means of preventing a single person or group from seizing control of the country. He advises the American people that, if they believe that it is necessary to modify the powers granted to the government through the Constitution, it should be done through constitutional amendments instead of through force.\n\n[[File:Valley Forge prayer.jpg|thumb|This 1866 engraving depicts Washington praying at [[Valley Forge]]]]\n\n=== Religion, morality and education ===\nOne of the most referenced parts of Washington's letter is his strong support of the importance of religion and morality in promoting private and public happiness and in promoting the political prosperity of the nation.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}} He argues that religious principles promote the protection of property, reputation, and life that are the foundations of justice. He cautions against the belief that the nation's morality can be maintained without religion:\n{{quote|Of all the dispositions and habits which lead to political prosperity, religion, and morality are indispensable supports. In vain would that man claim the tribute of patriotism, who should labor to subvert these great pillars of human happiness, these firmest props of the duties of men and citizens. The mere politician, equally with the pious man, ought to respect and to cherish them. A volume could not trace all their connections with private and public felicity. Let it simply be asked: Where is the security for property, for reputation, for life, if the sense of religious obligation desert the oaths which are the instruments of investigation in courts of justice? And let us with caution indulge the supposition that morality can be maintained without religion. Whatever may be conceded to the influence of refined education on minds of peculiar structure, reason and experience both forbid us to expect that national morality can prevail in exclusion of religious principle.<ref name=\"WashingtonFarewell\"/>}}\n\nWashington refers to religious principle as the foundation of public morality.  He also argues that the American government needs to ensure \"the general diffusion of knowledge\"<ref name=\"Farewell Address\" /> throughout the United States; the government has been created to enforce the opinion of the people, so the opinion of the people should be informed and knowledgeable.\n\n=== Credit and government borrowing ===\nWashington provides strong support for a balanced federal budget, arguing that the nation's credit is an important source of strength and security. He urges the American people to preserve the national credit by avoiding war, avoiding unnecessary borrowing, and paying off any national debt accumulated in times of war as quickly as possible in times of peace so that future generations do not have to take on the financial burdens. Despite his warnings to avoid taking on debt, Washington does state his belief that sometimes it is necessary to spend money to prevent dangers or wars that will cost more if not properly prepared for. At these times, he argues, it is necessary for the people to cooperate by paying taxes to cover these precautionary expenses. He emphasizes how important it is for the government to be careful in choosing the items that will be taxed, but also reminds the American people that, no matter how hard the government tries, there will never be a tax which is not inconvenient and unpleasant to those who must pay it.\n\n=== Foreign relations and free trade ===\nWashington dedicates a large part of his farewell address to discussing foreign relations and the dangers of permanent alliances between the United States and foreign nations, which he views as foreign entanglements.<ref>{{cite journal| first=Samuel Flagg| last=Bemis| title=Washington's Farewell Address: A Foreign Policy of Independence| journal=American Historical Review| date=1934| volume=39| issue=2| pages=250\u2013268| jstor=1838722}}</ref> He advocates a policy of good faith and justice towards all nations, again making reference to proper behavior based upon religious doctrine and morality. He urges the American people to avoid long-term friendly relations or rivalries with any nation, arguing that attachments with or animosity toward other nations will only cloud the government's judgment in its foreign policy. He argues that longstanding poor relations will only lead to unnecessary wars due to a tendency to blow minor offenses out of proportion when committed by nations viewed as enemies of the United States. He continues this argument by claiming that alliances are likely to draw the United States into wars that have no justification and no benefit to the country beyond simply defending the favored nation. Alliances, he warns, often lead to poor relations with nations who feel that they are not being treated as well as America's allies, and threaten to influence the American government into making decisions based upon the will of their allies instead of the will of the American people.\n[[Image:Edmond-Charles Gen\u00eat.png|thumb|right|150px|[[Edmond-Charles Gen\u00eat|Citizen Gen\u00eat]] was the French minister who interfered in U.S. politics]]\n\nWashington makes an extended reference to the dangers of foreign nations who will seek to influence the American people and government; nations who may be considered friendly as well as nations considered enemies will equally try to influence the government to do their will. \"Real patriots\", he warns, who \"resist the intrigues\" of foreign nations may find themselves \"suspected and odious\" in the eyes of others, yet he urges the people to stand firm against such influences all the same. He portrays those who attempt to further such foreign interests as becoming the \"tools and dupes\" of those nations, stealing the applause and praise of their country away from the \"real patriots\" while actually working to \"surrender\" American interests to foreign nations.\n\nWashington goes on to urge the American people to take advantage of their isolated position in the world, and to avoid attachments and entanglements in foreign affairs, especially those of Europe, which he argues have little or nothing to do with the interests of America. He argues that it makes no sense for the American people to become embroiled in European affairs when their isolated position and unity allow them to remain neutral and focus on their own affairs. He argues that the country should avoid permanent alliances with all foreign nations, although temporary alliances during times of extreme danger may be necessary. He states that current treaties should be honored but not extended.\n\nWashington wraps up his foreign policy stance by advocating free trade with all nations, arguing that trade links should be established naturally and the role of the government should be limited to ensuring stable trade, defending the rights of American merchants and any provisions necessary to ensure the conventional rules of trade.\n\n=== Address's intentions ===\nWashington uses this portion of the address to explain that he does not expect his advice to make any great impression upon the people or to change the course of American politics, but he does hope that the people will remember his devoted service to his country.\n\n=== Defense of the Proclamation of Neutrality ===\nWashington then explains his reasoning behind the [[Proclamation of Neutrality]] which he made during the [[French Revolutionary Wars]], despite the standing [[Treaty of Alliance (1778)|Treaty of Alliance]] with France. He explains that the United States had a right to remain neutral in the conflict and that the correctness of that decision \"has been virtually admitted by all\" nations since. Justice and humanity required him to remain neutral during the conflict, he argues, and the neutrality was also necessary to allow the new government a chance to mature and gain enough strength to control its own affairs.\n\n=== Closing thoughts ===\nWashington closes his letter to the American people by asking them to forgive any failures which may have occurred during his service to the country, assuring them that they were due to his own weaknesses and by no means intentional. The sentences express his excitement about joining his fellow Americans as a private citizen in the free government which they have created together during his 45 years of public service.\n\n== Legacy ==\n{{see|Post-presidency of George Washington}}\nWashington's Farewell Address is considered to be one of the most important documents in American history<ref name=\"loc.gov\"/> and the foundation of the Federalist Party's political doctrine.\n\nWashington later accepted a commission from President [[John Adams]], despite his stated desire to retire from public service, as the [[Commanding General of the United States Army|Senior Officer]] of a Provisional Army formed to defend the nation against a possible invasion by French forces during the [[Quasi-War]].<ref name=\"mountvernon.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.mountvernon.org/learn/meet_george/index.cfm/ss/21/ |title=A Brief Biography of George Washington |publisher=Mountvernon.org |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110823160852/http://www.mountvernon.org/learn/meet_george/index.cfm/ss/21 |archivedate=August 23, 2011 }}</ref> Washington held true to his statements in his farewell address, despite spending months organizing the Officer Corps of the Provisional Army, and declined suggestions that he return to public office in the [[1800 United States presidential election|presidential election of 1800]].<ref name=\"mountvernon.org\"/>\n\nWashington's statements on the importance of religion and morality in American politics and his warnings on the dangers of foreign alliances influenced political debates into the twentieth century,<ref name=\"loc.gov\"/> and have received special consideration as advice from an American hero.\n\n=== Alliances with foreign nations ===\nWashington's hope that the United States would end permanent alliances with foreign nations was realized in 1800 with the [[Convention of 1800]], the Treaty of Mortefontaine which officially ended the 1778 Treaty of Alliance, in exchange for ending the Quasi-War and establishing [[Most favoured nation|most favored nation]] trade relations with [[First French Empire|Napoleonic France]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xenophongroup.com/mcjoynt/alliance2.htm |title=Perspective On The French-American Alliance |publisher=Xenophongroup.com |date= |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090120014620/http://xenophongroup.com/mcjoynt/alliance2.htm |archive-date=January 20, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In 1823, Washington's foreign policy goals were further realized in the [[Monroe Doctrine]], which promised non-interference in European affairs so long as the nations of Europe did not seek to colonize or interfere with the newly independent Latin American nations of Central and [[South America]]. The United States did not enter into any permanent military alliances with foreign nations until the 1949 [[North Atlantic Treaty]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nato.int/docu/basictxt/treaty.htm |title=Online Library: North Atlantic Treaty Organization |publisher=Nato.int |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080913210131/http://www.nato.int/docu/basictxt/treaty.htm |archivedate=September 13, 2008 }}</ref> which formed [[NATO]].\n\n=== Reading in Congress ===\n[[Philadelphia]] residents signed a petition in January 1862 during the [[American Civil War]] requesting that Congress commemorate the 130th anniversary of Washington's birth by reading his Farewell Address \"in one or the other of the Houses of Congress.\"<ref name=\"Farewell Address\">{{cite web |url=http://www.access.gpo.gov/congress/senate/farewell/sd106-21.pdf |title=Washington's Farewell Address, Senate Document No. 106\u201321, Washington, 2000 |format=PDF |date= |accessdate=September 19, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090612002306/http://www.access.gpo.gov/congress/senate/farewell/sd106-21.pdf |archive-date=June 12, 2009 |url-status=dead }}{{Include-GPO}}</ref> It was first read in the House of Representatives in February 1862, and reading Washington's address became a tradition in both houses by 1899. The House of Representatives abandoned the practice in 1984,<ref name=\"Farewell Address\"/> but the Senate continues the tradition. [[Washington's Birthday]] is observed by selecting a member of the Senate to read the address aloud on the Senate floor, alternating between political parties each year since 1896.<ref name=\"Farewell Address\"/> Additionally, readers make an entry into a black, leather-bound journal maintained by the Secretary of the Senate upon finishing.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.senate.gov/artandhistory/history/minute/Washingtons_Farewell_Address.htm | title=U.S. Senate: Washington's Farewell Address | author=United States Senate}}</ref>\n\n== In popular culture ==\nAccording to political journalist [[John Avlon]], the Farewell Address was \"once celebrated as a civic Scripture, more widely reprinted than the Declaration of Independence\" but adds that it \"is now almost forgotten.\"<ref>{{cite book|first=John |last=Avlon|authorlink=John Avlon|title=Washington's Farewell: The Founding Father's Warning to Future Generations|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UGXUDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA1|year=2017|publisher=Simon and Schuster|page=1}}</ref> He suggested that it had long been \"eclipsed in the national memory\" until the Broadway musical ''[[Hamilton (musical)|Hamilton]]'' brought it back to popular awareness in the song \"[[One Last Time (Hamilton)|One Last Time]]\", where lines are sung by Washington and Hamilton from the end of the Address.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/01/08/508537167/what-we-can-learn-from-washingtons-farewell|title=What We Can Learn From 'Washington's Farewell'|last=|first=|date=January 8, 2017|work=All Things Considered|access-date=|publisher=National Public Radio|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Federalist Era]] which covers the 1790s\n* [[Republicanism in the United States]]\n* [[United States non-interventionism]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n{{main|Bibliography of George Washington}}\n* Avlon, John. ''Washington's Farewell: The Founding Father's Warning to Future Generations'' (2017) [https://www.amazon.com/dp/147674646X/  excerpt]\n* {{cite journal |last=DeConde |first=Alexander |title=Washington's Farewell, the French Alliance, and the Election of 1796 |journal=Mississippi Valley Historical Review |year=1957 |volume=43 |issue=4 |pages=641\u2013658 |issn=0161-391X |doi=10.2307/1902277}}\n* {{cite book |last=Gilbert |first=Felix |title=To the Farewell Address: Ideas of Early American Foreign Policy |year=1961 |location=New York |publisher=Harper and Row }}\n* Hostetler, Michael J. \"Washington's farewell address: Distance as bane and blessing\". ''Rhetoric & Public Affairs'' (2002) 5#3 pp: 393\u2013407. [http://mtw160-198.ippl.jhu.edu/journals/rhetoric_and_public_affairs/v005/5.3hostetler.pdf online]\n* Kaufman, Burton Ira, ed. (1969) ''Washington's Farewell Address: The View from the 20th Century'' (Quadrangle Books) essays by scholars\n* Malanson, Jeffrey J. (2015) ''Addressing America: George Washington's Farewell and the Making of National Culture, Politics, and Diplomacy, 1796\u20131852'' (Kent State University Press, 2015). x, 253 pp [https://www.amazon.com/Addressing-America-Washingtons-Diplomacy-1796-1852/dp/1606352512/ excerpt]\n* {{cite journal |last=Pessen |first=Edward |author-link=Edward Pessen |title=George Washington's Farewell Address, the Cold War, and the Timeless National |journal=Journal of the Early Republic |year=1987 |volume=7 |issue=1 |pages=1\u201327 |issn=0275-1275 |doi=10.2307/3123426}}\n* {{cite book |last=Spalding |first=Matthew |first2=Patrick J. |last2=Garrity |lastauthoramp=yes |title=A Sacred Union of Citizens: George Washington's Farewell Address and the American Character |location=Lanham, MD |publisher=Rowman & Littlefield |year=1996 |isbn=0-8476-8261-7 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/sacredunionofcit00spal }}\n* {{cite journal |last=Spalding |first=Matthew |authormask=3 |title=George Washington's Farewell Address |journal=[[The Wilson Quarterly]] |volume=20 |issue=4 |year=1996 |pages= |doi= }}\n* {{cite book |last=Varg |first=Paul A. |title=Foreign Policies of the Founding Fathers |year=1963 |location=Baltimore |publisher=Penguin Books|URL=https://archive.org/details/foreignpolicieso00varg_0 }}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote|George Washington}}\n* [https://www.loc.gov/item/mjm012832/  James Madison's manuscript of June 21 1792]\n* [https://www.presidency.ucsb.edu/node/200675 Text of Washington's Farewell Address]\n\n{{George Washington}}\n{{Alexander Hamilton}}\n{{authority control}}\n[[Category:1796 documents]]\n[[Category:1796 in politics]]\n[[Category:1796 in the United States]]\n[[Category:Farewell addresses]]\n[[Category:Non-interventionism]]\n[[Category:Presidency of George Washington]]\n[[Category:Speeches by George Washington|Farewell Address]]\n", "name_user": "2601:484:c000:a330:cd7:2a1a:269d:fccc", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Washington%27s_Farewell_Address"}
